 The Rise of Spanish |website=[[The Economist]] |date=1 June 2013}} \n* {{cite web |url=https://www.thoughtco.com/spanish-fewer-words-than-english-3079596 |title=Does Spanish Have Fewer Words Than English? |last=Erichsen |first=Gerald |date=20 May 2017 |website=ThoughtCo |publisher=[[Dotdash]]}}\n* {{Cite news|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2013/09/05/what-is-the-future-of-spanish-in-the-united-states/|title=What is the future of Spanish in the United States?|work=Pew Research Center|access-date=27 November 2018|language=en-US}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=Category:Spanish language\n|commons=Category:Spanish language\n|b=Subject:Spanish language\n|n=no\n|q=no\n|s=no\n|v=Topic:Spanish\n|voy=Spanish phrasebook\n|species=no\n|d=Q1321\n|mw=no\n|m=no\n}}\n{{InterWiki|code=es}}\n\n===Organizations===\n* [https://www.rae.es/ Real Academia Espa\u00f1ola (RAE)], Royal Spanish Academy. Spain's official institution, with a mission to ensure the stability of the Spanish language\n* [https://www.cervantes.es/default.htm Instituto Cervantes], Cervantes Institute. A Spanish government agency, responsible for promoting the study and the teaching of the Spanish language and culture.\n\n=== Courses and learning resources ===\n* SpanishBoom.com \u2013 [https://spanishboom.com/free-spanish-course/ Free Spanish course with audio]\n* BBC \u2013 [https://www.bbc.co.uk/languages/spanish/ Free Spanish learning resources]\n* Curlie.org \u2013 [https://curlie.org/Science/Social_Sciences/Linguistics/Languages/Natural/Indo-European/Italic/Romance/Spanish/ Directory of Spanish language resources]\n* WordReference.com [https://forum.wordreference.com/#spanish-english-espanol-ingles.23 Spanish-English forum]\n\n===Online dictionaries===\n* Royal Spanish Academy (RAE) \u2013 [https://dle.rae.es/ Monolingual Spanish dictionary]\n* SpanishBoom.com \u2013 [https://spanishboom.com/visual-spanish-dictionary/ Spanish-English visual dictionary with audio]\n* WordReference.com \u2013 [https://www.wordreference.com/English_Spanish_Dictionary.asp Spanish-English dictionary]\n\n===Articles and reports===\n* Instituto Cervantes [https://cvc.cervantes.es/lengua/espanol_lengua_viva/default.htm Annual reports on the status of the Spanish language around the world]\n* British Council [https://www.britishcouncil.org/voices-magazine/spanish-speak-language-400-million-people Spanish: speak the language of 400 million people]\n\n{{Spanish variants by continent}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Other languages\n|state=\n|list =\n{{Romance languages|state=collapsed}}\n{{Languages of Europe}}\n{{South America topic|Languages of}}\n{{Portal bar|Language}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spanish Language}}\n[[Category:Spanish language| ]]\n[[Category:Fusional languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Languages of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Languages of Chile]]\n[[Category:Languages of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Languages of Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:Languages of Cuba]]\n[[Category:Languages of the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:Languages of Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Languages of El Salvador]]\n[[Category:Languages of Equatorial Guinea]]\n[[Category:Languages of Guatemala]]\n[[Category:Languages of Honduras]]\n[[Category:Languages of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Languages of Nicaragua]]\n[[Category:Languages of Panama]]\n[[Category:Languages of Paraguay]]\n[[Category:Languages of Peru]]\n[[Category:Languages of Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Languages of South America]]\n[[Category:Languages of Spain]]\n[[Category:Languages of the United States]]\n[[Category:Languages of Uruguay]]\n[[Category:Languages of Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Subject\u2013verb\u2013object languages]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4072:e:214c:b04d:3352:571b:8a6b", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spanish_language"}
{"title_page": "Boxing on ABC", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n|show_name            = ''Boxing on ABC''\n|image                = \n|caption              = \n|show_name_2          = ABC Sports Pro Boxing\n|genre                = [[Professional boxing]] bouts\n|creator              = \n|developer            = \n|director             = \n|starring             = {{ubl|[[Don Chevrier]]|[[Howard Cosell]]|[[Dan Dierdorf]]|[[Keith Jackson]]|[[Jim Lampley]]|[[Al Michaels]]|[[Jerry Quarry]]|[[Chris Schenkel]]|[[Al Trautwig]]|[[Alex Wallau]]}}\n|theme_music_composer = \n|opentheme            = \n|endtheme             =\n|composer             = \n|country              = [[United States]]\n|language             = [[English language|English]]\n|num_seasons          = \n|num_episodes         = \n|list_episodes        = \n|executive_producer   = \n|producer             = \n|location             = \n|camera               = [[Multi-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n|runtime              = Various\n|company              = [[ESPN on ABC|ABC Sports]]\n|distributor          = \n|channel              = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n|picture_format       = [[Color]]\n|first_aired          = {{Start date|1964|11|11}}\n|last_aired           = {{End date|2000|6|17}}\n|preceded_by          = \n|followed_by          = \n|related              = ''[[Wide World of Sports (American TV program)|Wide World of Sports]]''\n|website              = https://abcnews.go.com/search?searchtext=Boxing\n}}\n\n'''''Boxing on ABC''''' refers to a series of [[boxing]] events<ref>{{cite book |last=Rapak|first=Dan|date= |title=Brought to You by . . .|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dH40Fl8vG2IC&pg=PA363&dq=ABC+Sports+Boxing&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi24Y3qk4zkAhVQgK0KHVWDCyc4WhDoATAFegQIAxAC#v=onepage&q=ABC%20Sports%20Boxing&f=false|location= |publisher=AuthorHouse|page=363|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref> that have been televised on the [[American Broadcasting Company]]. Many of these events aired under the ''[[Wide World of Sports (American TV series)|Wide World of Sports]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boxrec.com/media/index.php/ABC's_Wide_World_of_Sports_Televised_Fights|title=ABC's Wide World of Sports Televised Fights|last= |first= |date= |website=BoxRec.com|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> banner which began on April 11, 1964 when challenger [[Muhammad Ali]], then known as Cassius Clay, [[Muhammad Ali vs. Sonny Liston|defeated]] champion [[Sonny Liston]] in the seventh round. ABC's final boxing card occurred on June 17, 2000<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxingscene.com/antonio-tarver-speaks-on-fight-postponement--8193|title=Antonio Tarver Speaks on Fight Postponement|last=Vester|first=Mark|date=April 13, 2007|website=BoxingScene.com|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|title=Jose Luis Castillo vs Stevie Johnston - 1/3|id=7zQaFh9QhQM&t}}</ref>.\n\n==History==\n===''Tomorrow's Boxing Champions'' (1949-50)===\nThe first incarnation of boxing telecasts on ABC was ''Tomorrow's Boxing Champions'', which aired on Tuesday nights beginning in January 1949. Originating from [[Chicago]], the program featured young, unranked fighters. [[Bob Elson]] did the blow-by-blow commentary. The series concluded in September 1950.\n\n===''Meet the Champ'' (1952)===\nIn January 1952, ABC premiered ''Meet the Champ'', which was a collection of bouts involving members of the [[United States Armed Forces|armed forces]]. The program aired on Thursday nights, with Wally Butterfield announcing.\n\n===''Saturday Night Fights'' (1953-55)===\nIn 1953, [[Ray Arcel]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Kriegel|first=Mark|date= |title=The Good Son: The Life of Ray \"Boom Boom\" Mancini|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yzN94ZdYV8oC&pg=PA90&dq=ABC+Sports+Boxing&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi24Y3qk4zkAhVQgK0KHVWDCyc4WhDoATAJegQIBxAC#v=onepage&q=ABC%20Sports%20Boxing&f=false|location= |publisher=Simon and Schuster|page=90|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref> began promoting bouts on ABC. Unfortunately, shortly after arranging the fights for ABC<ref>{{cite book |last=Dewey|first=Donald|date= |title=Ray Arcel: A Boxing Biography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GQsHqHfqcq4C&pg=PA152&lpg=PA152&dq=ray+arcel+abc&source=bl&ots=wfsRPRj1Ps&sig=ACfU3U1Y2NmSWL-iMC_Iv8mFufBI5u4zRw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjeqt-nlozkAhVIgK0KHYcUAyo4ChDoATAAegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=ray%20arcel%20abc&f=false|location= |publisher=McFarland|page=152|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref>, Arcel<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibhof.com/pages/about/inductees/nonparticipant/arcel.html|title=Ray Arcel |last= |first= |date= |website=International Boxing Hall of Fame|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> ran afoul of organized crime. The matches on ABC competed with other network television fights run by the [[International Boxing Club]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxing.com/ray_arcel_the_dean_of_them_all.html|title=Ray Arcel: Dean of Them All|last=Ecksel|first=Robert|date=January 8, 2013 |website=Boxing.com|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> (IBC), who were reputed to have underworld ties.\n\n[[Bill Stern]] did blow-by-blow commentary when ''Saturday Night Fights'' premiered. Come the fall, Jack Gregson took over from Stern.\n\n===''Boxing from Ridgewood Grove'' and ''Motor City Boxing'' (1953)===\nIn February 1953, ABC premiered ''Boxing from Ridgewood Grove''. It aired on Tuesdays nights, with [[Jason Owen]] as the announcer in the first month and Bob Finnegan taking over until its cancellation in August. In March 1953, ABC brought ''Motor City Boxing'' from [[Detroit]]. The program would air for three months of Thursdays, with Don Wattrick at the providing commentary.\n\n===''Boxing from Eastern Parkway'' (1954)===\nIn May 1954, ''[[Boxing from Eastern Parkway]]'' moved from the [[DuMont Television Network]] to ABC. Tommy Logran handled the blow-by-blow commentary while occasionally being helped by Bob Finnegan and Fred Sayles. The series ended when ABC failed to renew its contract with the arena after picking up the rights to show fights at the [[International Boxing Club]].<ref name=\"BrooksMarsh2009\">{{cite book|author1=Tim Brooks|author2=Earle F. Marsh|title=The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network and Cable TV Shows, 1946-Present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w8KztFy6QYwC&pg=PA174|date=24 June 2009|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-48320-1|page=174}}</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5wQsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=esYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1251%2C4906110 \"Eastern Parkway Finished\"], [[Associated Press]] in ''[[TimesDaily]]'', May 17, 1955.</ref>\n\n===''The Wednesday Night Fights'' (1955-60)===\nAfter cancellation of ''[[Pabst Blue Ribbon Bouts]]'' on CBS in 1955, the series was picked up by ABC, renamed ''The Wednesday Night Fights'',<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w8KztFy6QYwC&lpg=PA174&pg=PA174|title=The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network and Cable TV Shows, 1946-Present|last=Brooks|first=Tim|last2=Marsh|first2=Earle F.|date=2009-06-24|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=9780307483201|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Mee|first=Bob|date= |title=Ali and Liston: The Boy Who Would Be King and the Ugly Bear|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PUAS56Z-51EC&pg=PA45&dq=Boxing+on+ABC&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjOxO_ojI7kAhVSL6wKHSChAqk4bhDoATAJegQIABAC#v=onepage&q=Boxing%20on%20ABC&f=false|location= |publisher=Skyhorse Publishing Inc.|page=45|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref> and continued until 1960.\n\n[[Russ Hodges]] and [[Jack Drees]] both stayed with the show when it transferred from CBS. Hodges however, left in October 1955 and Drees was the only regular announcer for the five years it stayed on ABC.\n\n===''Fight of the Week'' (1960-63)===\nAfter [[NBC]]-TV's cancellation of ''[[Gillette Cavalcade of Sports|The Gillette Cavalcade of Sports]]'' in the spring of [[1960 in television|1960]], ABC took over the [[prime time]] boxing program, although it was renamed ''[[Fight of the Week]]''. Legendary boxing commentator [[Don Dunphy]] did the blow-by-blow description of the bouts, which took place on Saturday beginning in October 1960 and running through September 1963. \n\nFrom there, the series moved to Friday nights, where it continued until ABC finally canceled prime time boxing after the bout of September 11, 1964, permanently ending 18 years of regularly scheduled prime time boxing on [[United States|U.S.]] broadcast network television. One reason for the downturn of televised boxing occurred on ''Fight of the Week'''s [[Benny Paret vs. Emile Griffith III|the March 24, 1962 broadcast]], when [[Emile Griffith]] defeated [[Benny Paret|Benny \"The Kid\" Paret]] for the Welterweight Championship at [[New York City|New York]]'s [[Madison Square Garden]]. Paret was carried from the ring unconscious, and died several days later as a result of his injuries that he had sustained in that bout.\n\n===''Wide World of Sports'' (1964-2000)===\nPrior to the advent of ''Wide World of Sports'', many major [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|heavyweight boxing title]] matches were televised via \u201c[[Closed-circuit television|closed-circuit]]\u201d (this generally meant that you had go to a movie theater to see it, pay a decent-sized amount of money to get it, and then watch it on a giant screen). Often, ''Wide World of Sports'' would show full-length replays of the fights a week or two later; these replays were usually called by [[Howard Cosell]], who became one of the best-known (and possibly most controversial) sportscaster in American television history.\n\n[[Jerry Quarry]] retired for over two and a half years after his 1975 fight with [[Ken Norton]] fight. At around this time, Quarry signed a contract with ABC to be a boxing commentator. Quarry was very popular in this position, drawing the ire of Howard Cosell, an ABC commentator being pushed out of some work by Quarry. In mid-1977, a return match was being put together which would put Quarry in against a ranked heavyweight. The ranked heavyweight would be Italian Lorenzo Zanon. The match was to be televised on ABC, where Quarry was contracted. But both fighters signed to have the bout televised on [[Boxing on CBS|CBS]]. When Quarry, who often negotiated his own fight contracts, signed the bout to CBS, he lost his ABC contract. \n\nIn 1976, ABC made a deal with promoter [[Don King (boxing promoter)|Don King]] and [[The Ring (magazine)|''The Ring'' magazine]] to stage a tournament<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.si.com/more-sports/2014/10/31/al-michaels-howard-cosell-you-cant-make-excerpt|title=Book excerpt: Al Michaels reflects on his time with Howard Cosell|last=Michaels, Wertheim|first=Al, L. Jon|date=October 31, 2014|website=Sports Illustrated|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> to determine the best fighter from the U.S. in each weight division. The tournament, dubbed the United States Boxing Championships was scheduled to begin on January 16, 1977 with ABC agreeing to finance the tournament with an investment of between $1.5 million and $2 million<ref>\n{{cite book |last=Heller|first=Peter|date= |title=Bad Intentions: The Mike Tyson Story|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zQeJ5T9cGoAC&pg=PA211&dq=1977+ring+magazine+abc+don+king&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjI05eKk47kAhVHSq0KHQZSBFUQ6AEwBHoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=1977%20ring%20magazine%20abc%20don%20king&f=false|location= |publisher=Da Capo Press, Incorporated|page=211|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref>. Soon however, it determined that King was essentially using the tournament to sign the best fighters to exclusive contracts. To make matters worse, ''The Ring'' was falsifying records and inflating rankings as a means of getting a number of fighters into the tournament for King.\n\n[[Sugar Ray Leonard]]'s bout with [[Wilfred Ben\u00edtez]] on November 30, 1979<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thefightcity.com/benitez-vs-leonard/|title=Nov. 30, 1979: Benitez vs Leonard -- Sugar Ray Wins|last= Portis|first=Robert|date=November 30, 2018|website=The Fight City|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> marked the first time in the era of big-money sports events that a non-heavyweight fight would be carried as the main event on [[prime time]] television<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.si.com/vault/1979/11/26/824205/sugar-sure-is-sweet-in-driving-toward-a-welterweight-title-shot-ray-leonard-has-evoked-another-sugar-ray-and-that-venerable-leonard-benny|title=SUGAR SURE IS SWEET|last=Mack|first=William|date=November 26, 1979|website=Sports Illustrated|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxinginsider.com/columns/boxing-on-primetime-network-tv-when-boxing-really-hit-paydirt/|title=Boxing on Primetime Network TV? When Boxing Really Hit Paydirt|last=Charles|first=Jay|date=January 23, 2013|website=Boxing Insider|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>.\n\nOn November 15, 1984, ABC broadcast 'A Night of Gold', a card from promoter [[Dan Duva]]'s 'Main Events'<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2014/11/14/7173919/olympic-article-part-2|title=Boxing History: 30th Anniversary of 'A Night of Gold' Part One|last=McLachlan|first=Kyle|date=November 14, 2014|website=Bad Left Hook|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>, featuring no less than four gold medal winners ([[Mark Breland]], [[Tyrell Biggs]], [[Pernell Whitaker]] and [[Meldrick Taylor]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Katz|first=Michael|date=November 15, 1984|title=HOLYFIELD FUTURE IS IN HIS HANDS|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/11/15/sports/holyfield-future-is-in-his-hands.html|work=The New York Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref>) from that year's [[Boxing at the 1984 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympic games]], as well as those lagging behind in the runners-up spots.\n\nIn 1992, ABC announced plans to counterprogram<ref>{{cite news |last=Williams|first=Jennifer|date=February 7, 1992|title=CBS ANNOUNCERS ARE READY FOR OLYMPICS|url=https://www.dailypress.com/news/dp-xpm-19920207-1992-02-07-9202070180-story.html|work=Daily Press|location= |access-date= }}</ref> the [[1992 Winter Olympics|Winter Olympics]] on [[CBS Olympic broadcasts|CBS]] with boxing, a sport at that point, seldom seen on network television. This particular boxing series was sponsored by [[Fruit of the Loom]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart|first=Larry|date=February 7, 1992 |title=No Need to Coach Fratello for TV|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1992-02-07-sp-1329-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Nidetz|first=Steve|date=January 6, 1992|title=ABC SAW NO DOLLAR SENSE IN OLYMPICS|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1992-01-06-9201020585-story.html|work=Chicago Tribune|location= |access-date= }}</ref>. ABC proceeded to forgo the typical [[United States dollar|$]]300,000 rights fees of the prior year, and instead, set a $75,000 limit and scheduled three consecutive Saturdays of action<ref>{{cite news |last=Craig|first=Jack|date=February 16, 1992|title=Some, networks included, see fight game gaining from Tyson's loss|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/bs-xpm-1992-02-16-1992047146-story.html|work=The Baltimore Sun|location= |access-date= }}</ref>.\n\n====Notable bouts====\n{{main|List of events broadcast on Wide World of Sports (American TV series)}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|'''Year'''\n|'''Day'''\n|'''Event'''\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1964\n|April 11\n|Challenger [[Cassius Clay]], soon to adopt the [[Muslim]] name of Muhammad Ali, knocks out champion [[Sonny Liston]] in the [[Muhammad Ali versus Sonny Liston#The first fight|seventh round]] in [[Miami Beach, Florida]].\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Sonny Liston}}\n|-\n|May 30\n|[[U.S. Olympic Boxing Trials]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=1988 U S Olympic Boxing Trials|id=ZwKBU57C58g}}</ref>. \n|-\n|1965\n|May 29\n|The [[Muhammad Ali versus Sonny Liston#The second bout|rematch]] between [[Muhammad Ali]] and [[Sonny Liston]] from [[Lewiston, Maine]].\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|1966\n|April 2\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] defeats [[George Chuvalo]] in a 15-round decision to retain his [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] in [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], Canada.\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. George Chuvalo}}\n|-\n|May 21\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] retains his [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] title with a sixth-round TKO of [[Henry Cooper]] in London.\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Henry Cooper}}\n|-\n|September 10\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] defeats [[Karl Mildenberger]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Muhammad Ali vs Karl Mildenberger 1966-09-10|id=u0bbw5J4fjU}}</ref> in a [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|heavyweight title]] defense, live from [[Frankfurt]], [[West Germany]] with a 12th-round TKO.\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Karl Mildenberger}}\n|-\n|November 26\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] defends his [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|world heavyweight title]] for the sixth time in 1966 on ''Wide World of Sports'' against [[Cleveland Williams]].\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Cleveland Williams}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1967\n|February 11\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] defends his [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] against [[Ernie Terrell]] in [[Houston]], [[Texas]].\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Ernie Terrell}}\n|-\n|March 11\n|Interview with [[Muhammad Ali]] and [[Wilt Chamberlain]].\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1970\n|February 21\n|[[Joe Frazier]] knocks out [[Jimmy Ellis (boxer)|Jimmy Ellis]] in the fifth round for the vacant [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] from New York City.\n|-\n|October 31\n|In [[Atlanta]], [[Muhammad Ali]] defeats [[Jerry Quarry]] in the third round, in his first fight in three years.\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Jerry Quarry}}\n|-\n|November 21\n|[[Joe Frazier]] knocks out [[Bob Foster (boxer)|Bob Foster]] in the second round of their [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] fight in [[Detroit]].\n|-\n|1971\n|March 13\n|Analysis of the [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] [[Fight of the Century|fight]] between [[Muhammad Ali]] and [[Joe Frazier]] with Muhammad Ali. \n{{main|Fight of the Century}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1972\n|September 23\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] ends the career of former [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|world heavyweight champion]] [[Floyd Patterson]] with a seventh-round knockout in New York City.\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Floyd Patterson}}\n|-\n|November 25\n|[[Muhammad Ali]]-[[Bob Foster (boxer)|Bob Foster]] fight.\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Bob Foster}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1973\n|January 27\n|[[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] fight between [[Joe Frazier]] and [[George Foreman]] from [[Kingston, Jamaica]].\n{{main|Joe Frazier vs. George Foreman}}\n|-\n|March 31\n|[[Ken Norton]] wins a 12-round decision against [[Muhammad Ali]] in their heavyweight fight from [[San Diego]], [[California]].\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Ken Norton}}\n|-\n|September 15\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] wins his rematch with [[Ken Norton]] rematch in 12 rounds.\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|1974\n|January 26\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] and [[Joe Frazier]] scuffle<ref>{{cite book |last=Hudson Jr.|first=David L.|date= |title=Boxing in America: An Autopsy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VcKGH5Oju1gC&pg=PA70&dq=Boxing+on+ABC+Sports&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiQuuLYj47kAhVRmK0KHYvbDpkQ6AEwB3oECAcQAg#v=onepage&q=Boxing%20on%20ABC%20Sports&f=false|location= |publisher= ABC-CLIO|page=70|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|title=ABC Wide World of Sports - Ali Frazier Studio Brawl|id=2Dh72Os_97c}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|title=Muhammad Ali and Joe Frazier Wide World Of Sports Studio Brawl 1974|id=0-u_Q3eVYU0}}</ref> during the telecast as they watch tape of their [[Fight of the Century|first fight]] in 1971.\n|- \n|March 2\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] defeats [[Joe Frazier]] in their [[Ali-Frazier II|second fight]] in New York City.\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Joe Frazier II}}\n|-\n|March 16\n|[[Roberto Dur\u00e1n]] knocks out [[Esteban De Jes\u00fas]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Roberto Duran vs Esteban De Jesus II|id=0K3nJBxwttk}}</ref> in the 11th round to retain his [[List of lightweight boxing champions|World Lightweight championship]] from [[Panama City]], [[Panama]].\n|-\n|March 31\n|[[George Foreman]] scores a second-round TKO of [[Ken Norton]] in a [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] fight.\n{{main|George Foreman vs. Ken Norton}}\n|-\n|September 21\n|''Wide World of Sports'' returns to [[Havana]], [[Cuba]] for the [[1974 World Amateur Boxing Championships|World Boxing Championships]], which featured [[Te\u00f3filo Stevenson]].\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|1975\n|January 5\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] knocks out [[George Foreman]] in the [[The Rumble in the Jungle|eighth round]] to reclaim the [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight]] title from [[Kinshasa]], [[Zaire]].\n{{main|The Rumble in the Jungle}}\n|-\n|March 29\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] scores a 15th-round TKO of [[Chuck Wepner]] in their [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] fight.\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Chuck Wepner}}\n|-\n|July 26\n|Coverage of the [[North American Continental Boxing Championships]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=1985 North American Boxing Championship|id=_eq1I7BYcWI}}</ref>. \n|-\n|September 13\n|[[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] fight between [[Muhammad Ali]] and [[Joe Bugner]] from [[Kuala Lampur]], [[Malaysia]].\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Joe Bugner}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1976<ref>{{cite book |last=Newfield|first=Jack|date= |title=The Life and Crimes of Don King: The Shame of Boxing in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sWYN6cETROQC&pg=PA105&dq=ABC+Sports+Boxing&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjI477bkIzkAhUB0KwKHbMNB2kQ6AEwBnoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=ABC%20Sports%20Boxing&f=false|location= |publisher= UNET 2 Corporation|page=105|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref>\n|January 11\n|''Wide World of Sports'' telecasts tape of [[Muhammad Ali]] defeating [[Joe Frazier]] in the \"[[Thrilla in Manila|Thriller in Manilla]]\" heavyweight title fight. \n{{main|Thrilla in Manila}}\n|-\n|October 2\n|Exclusive ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' still photographs of the Muhammad Ali-Ken Norton heavyweight fight and interviews with [[Ken Norton]], [[Joe Frazier]] and [[George Foreman]].\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1977\n|January 2\n|Interview with [[Muhammad Ali]].\n|-\n|May 14\n|[[Sugar Ray Leonard]] defeats [[Willie Rodriguez]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Sugar Ray Leonard vs Willie Rodriguez.avi|id=_zf1v4yIYKs}}</ref> in the second fight of his professional career. \n|-\n|1978\n|February 12\n|USA-Cuba Amateur boxing marks the first live telecast from Cuba since [[Fidel Castro|Castro]] came to power in 1959.\n|-\n|1979\n|February 4\n|[[Alexis Arg\u00fcello]] and [[Alfredo Escalera]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=The Bloody Battle Of Bayamon: Alexis Arguello vs Alfredo Escalera|id=8ipr2Ev3wa8}}</ref> for the [[List of WBC world champions#Super featherweight|WBC Super Featherweight]] title. Arguello retained his title with a 13th-round knockout.\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1980\n|July 19\n|[[Sugar Ray Leonard]] and [[Roberto Dur\u00e1n]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Roberto Duran vs Sugar Ray Leonard/ ABC Wide World Of Sports Leonard vs Duran w:Cosell|id=guTzuum-h40}}</ref> fight for the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] [[List of welterweight boxing champions|Welterweight Championship]].\n{{main|Sugar Ray Leonard vs. Roberto Dur\u00e1n II}}\n|-\n|September 27\n|In his second bid for the [[World Boxing Association|WBA]]/[[World Boxing Council|WBC]] [[List of middleweight boxing champions|Middleweight championship]], [[Marvelous Marvin Hagler]] scores a third-round TKO of [[Alan Minter]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Marvin Hagler -vs- Alan Minter 10/6/80|id=CfcxEHcP-Zw}}</ref> in a fight marred by a crowd riot.\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1981\n|September 5\n|[[Salvador S\u00e1nchez]] retains his [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] [[List of featherweight boxing champions|Featherweight Championship]] with a victory over [[Wilfredo G\u00f3mez]]. \n|-\n|October 17\n|[[Sugar Ray Leonard]] scores a 14th-round TKO of [[Thomas Hearns]] in a [[World Boxing Council|WBC]]/[[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[List of welterweight boxing champions|Welterweight Championship]] [[Sugar Ray Leonard vs. Thomas Hearns|fight]].\n{{main|Sugar Ray Leonard vs. Thomas Hearns}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1982\n|November 27\n|[[Te\u00f3filo Stevenson]] fights [[Tyrell Biggs]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Teofilo Stevenson {{!}} Tyrell Biggs I (a) 1/2|id=g_b9S4nZOe4}}</ref> from [[Reno, Nevada|Reno, Nev.]]\n|-\n|December 11\n|[[Rafael Lim\u00f3n|Bazooka Lim\u00f3n]] loses his [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] [[List of super featherweight boxing champions|Super Featherweight Championship]] to [[Bobby Chacon]] in a 15-round decision, while [[Wilfredo G\u00f3mez]] retained his WBC [[List of super bantamweight boxing champions|Super Bantamweight title]] against [[Lupe Pinto]].\n|-\n|1984\n|February 18\n|The USA-Cuba amateur boxing matches<ref>{{YouTube|title=USA vs Cuba ABC \u201cWide World of Sports\u201d 1984|id=4kZ1beq1RUo}}</ref> from [[Reno, Nevada|Reno]].\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|1985\n|January 5\n|Live coverage of [[Mark Breland]]'s second professional fight against [[Marlon Palmer]] in [[Atlantic City, New Jersey|Atlantic City, N.J.]].\n|-\n|January 20\n|Second professional fights of [[Pernell Whitaker]] (vs [[Danny Avery]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Pernell Whitaker {{!}} Danny Avery 1/2|id=fiTh7FYYDbo}}</ref>), [[Evander Holyfield]] (vs [[Eric Winbush]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Evander Holyfield vs Eric Winbush Full Fight (HD)|id=LsKQzxfgfBs}}</ref>) and [[Meldrick Taylor]] (vs [[Dwight Pratchett]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Meldrick Taylor (2nd pro fight) vs. Dwight Pratchett - 1/20/1985 = Boxing|id=QDWJYrqaX50}}</ref>), live, from [[Atlantic City, New Jersey|Atlantic City]].\n|-\n|April 20\n|The second professional fight of Olympic gold medalist [[Tyrell Biggs]].\n|-\n|June 8\n|[[Barry McGuigan]] defeats [[Eusebio Pedroza]] to claim the [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[List of welterweight boxing champions|Welterweight title]] in London.\n|-\n|September 28\n|[[Barry McGuigan]] defends his [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[List of welterweight boxing champions|Welterweight title]] against [[Bernard Taylor (boxer)|Bernard Taylor]] in [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]].\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|1986\n|February 15\n|[[Barry McGuigan]] defends his [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[List of welterweight boxing champions|Welterweight title]] against [[Danilo Cabreira]] in [[Dublin]], Ireland.\n|-\n|March 29\n|In a delayed broadcast, [[\"Marvelous\" Marvin Hagler]] knocks out [[John \"The Beast\" Mugabi]] in the 11th-round of their [[List of middleweight boxing champions|World Middleweight Championship]].\n|-\n|July 12\n|[[Evander Holyfield]] wins his first world title with a 15-round decision against [[Dwight Qawi]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Dwight Muhammad Qawi vs Evander Holyfield I|id=7_iYdUlCJ8&t}}</ref> for the [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[List of cruiserweight boxing champions|Junior Heavyweight]] crown live from [[Atlanta]].\n{{main|Dwight Muhammad Qawi vs. Evander Holyfield}}\n|-\n|July 26\n|[[Mike Tyson]] destroys [[Marvis Frazier]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Mike Tyson vs Marvis Frazier \u1d34\u1d30 - BEST QUALITY AVAILABLE|id=CRCVwsIokEw}}</ref> with a first-round knockout in their live heavyweight fight from [[Glens Falls, New York|Glens Falls, N.Y.]] In the same show, [[Barry McGuigan]] loses his [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[List of welterweight boxing champions|Welterweight]] crown in a 15-round decision to [[Steve Cruz (boxer)|Steve Cruz]] in [[Las Vegas Strip|Las Vegas]].\n{{main|Mike Tyson vs. Marvis Frazier}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1989\n|March 4\n|[[Virgil Hill]]-[[Bobby Czyz]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=VIRGIL HILL VS BOBBY CZYZ|id=V6yXrA6umME}}</ref> fight for the [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[List of light heavyweight boxing champions|Light Heavyweight Championship]] in [[Bismarck, North Dakota]].\n|-\n|April 1\n|[[Evander Holyfield]]-[[Michael Dokes]] heavyweight fight and a live studio interview with Holyfield.\n|-\n|June 24\n|[[Dennis Andries]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Hurley|first=Matthew|date= |title=Ringside Reflections|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NSH6AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA67&dq=Boxing+on+ABC&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjOxO_ojI7kAhVSL6wKHSChAqk4bhDoATAHegQIBhAC#v=onepage&q=Boxing%20on%20ABC&f=false|location= |publisher=|page=67|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref>-[[Jeff Harding (boxer)|Jeff Harding]] for the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] [[List of light heavyweight boxing champions|Light Heavyweight titles]].\n|-\n|1990\n|March 31\n|[[Meldrick Taylor]] fights [[Julio C\u00e9sar Ch\u00e1vez]] for the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]]/[[International Boxing Federation|IBF]] [[List of super lightweight boxing champions|Junior Welterweight/Super Lightweight]] titles.\n{{main|Julio C\u00e9sar Ch\u00e1vez vs. Meldrick Taylor}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1991\n|March 2\n|[[Riddick Bowe]] versus [[Tyrell Biggs]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Riddick Bowe vs Tyrell Biggs|id=ArLFL3o5rA0}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|title=Riddick Bowe vs Tyrell Biggs [1/3]|id=uCSR2LY34IU}}</ref>.\n{{main|Riddick Bowe vs. Michael Dokes}}\n|-\n|June 1\n|[[Mike Tyson]] scores a [[Knockout|TKO]] of [[Donovan Ruddock|Razor Ruddock]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=1991 03 18 Mike Tyson & Donovan Ruddock|id=sm2_7k9e7NE}}</ref> in a heavyweight fight, taped on March 18.\n{{main|Mike Tyson vs. Donovan Ruddock}}\n|-\n|1992\n|February 1\n|A special report on [[Mike Tyson]]'s trial and conviction of rape.\n|-\n|1993\n|March 6\n|[[Riddick Bowe]] knocks out [[Evander Holyfield]] in the 11th-round of their fight from [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]]. \n{{main|Evander Holyfield vs. Riddick Bowe}}\n|-\n|1995<ref>{{YouTube|title=1995 ABC WBO Boxing commercial|id=Ml7LGdWceA4}}</ref>\n|July 22\n|[[Mike Tyson]] retrospective: one month before his return to the ring.\n|-\n|1997\n|April 19\n|''Wide World'' airs network television's first women's professional boxing match. Former kickboxer [[Yvonne Trevino]] wins the [[Women's International Boxing Federation|WIBF]] Superflyweight championship live from [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]] in a first-round TKO over [[Brenda Rouse]]. \n|-\n|2000\n|June 17\n|[[Jos\u00e9 Luis Castillo]] upsets [[Stevie Johnston]] in the lightweight championship bout in [[Bell Gardens, California]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/sports/boxing/columns/story?columnist=rafael_dan&id=2808676|title=Tarver fight on ABC might revive boxing on network TV|last=Rafael|first=Dan|date=March 23, 2007|website=ESPN.com|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>. \n|}\n\n====Commentators====\n{{see also|List_of_sports_announcers#Boxing|List of Wide World of Sports (American TV series) announcers}}\n\n*[[Don Chevrier]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Houston|first=William|date=December 18, 2007|title='Voice of God' silenced|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/voice-of-god-silenced/article20407174/|work=The Globe and Mail|location= |access-date= }} </ref>\n\n*[[Dan Dierdorf]] - In April 1987, Dierdorf was hired by [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] to join [[Al Michaels]] and [[Frank Gifford]] on ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' broadcasts.<ref name=Dream>{{cite news|title=Dierdorf Has Dream Come True|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|date=April 14, 1987|page=5B|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/6975835/dierdorf_has_dream_come_true/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> He spent 12 seasons on ''Monday Night Football'' before resigning the post in early 1999.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dierdorf leaves \"Monday Night Football\" team: Lack of progress on contract prompts St. Louisan to step down|author=Dan Caesar|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|date=February 5, 1999|pages=D1, D7|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/6980135/dierdorf_leaves_monday_night_football/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> During his affiliation with ABC, Dierdorf also served as a blow-by-blow [[boxing]] commentator in 1989, beginning with [[Meldrick Taylor]]'s first defense of his championship, served as a correspondent for the network's coverage of the [[1988 Winter Olympics]] in [[Calgary]], and called play-by-play of some ''[[College Football on ABC]]'' games in the early 1990s.\n\n*[[Keith Jackson]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Boxing - 1985 - Keith Jackson Interviews Welterwt Mark Breland Before Hedgemon Robertson Fight|id=pm6erQ6FDPM}}</ref> - Though best known for his college football broadcasts, Jackson announced numerous other sports for ABC throughout his career, including [[Major League Baseball on ABC|Major League Baseball]], [[NBA on ABC|NBA basketball]], [[boxing]], [[auto racing]], [[PGA Tour on ABC|PGA Tour golf]], the [[United States Football League on ABC|USFL]], and the [[Olympics on ABC|Olympic Games]]. Jackson was a regular part of ABC's popular ''[[Wide World of Sports (US TV series)|Wide World of Sports]]'' (''WWOS''), covering both popular sports and obscure events like wrist wrestling. He also handled ''WWOS''' first coverage of boxer [[Sugar Ray Leonard]] at the North American Continental Boxing Championships on July 26, 1975, who Jackson called a young boxer to watch.<ref name=ABC70s>[http://espn.go.com/abcsports/wwos/milestones/1970s.html Wide World of Sports Highlights -- 1970s], ABC Sports Online, Accessed August 20, 2007.</ref> \n\n*[[Jim Lampley]]<ref>\n{{cite book |last=Early|first=Gerald|date= |title=The Cambridge Companion to Boxing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=axF9DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA304&dq=boxing+on+abc+wide+world+of+sports&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj74_COlo7kAhUG7qwKHd2tC2IQ6AEwAHoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=boxing%20on%20abc%20wide%20world%20of%20sports&f=false|location= |publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=304|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibhof.com/pages/about/inductees/observer/lampley.html|title=Jim Lampley|last= |first= |date= |website=International Boxing Hall of Fame|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|title=Boxing - ABC Review - Welterweight Title - Tomas Hearns VS Sugar Ray Leonard imasportsphile.com|id=521fBpPHmbk}}</ref> - In 1974, while in graduate school, he was chosen along with Don Tollefson in what [[ABC Sports|ABC]] called a ''talent hunt''. ABC executives thought that Lampley's youthful looks would make him endearing to the college crowds they looked to attract for their [[College Football on ABC|college football]] games. At ABC, he covered such events as [[Major League Baseball on ABC|Major League Baseball]] and [[College Basketball on ABC|college basketball]] games, the [[1986 Indianapolis 500|1986]] and [[1987 Indianapolis 500|1987]] [[Indianapolis 500]], the 1977 [[Monon Bell]] game between [[DePauw University]] and [[Wabash College]], five [[Olympics on ABC|Olympics]], as well as the program ''[[Wide World of Sports (US TV series)|Wide World of Sports]]''.\n\n*[[Al Michaels]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Stevie Johnston vs Jose Luis Castillo I|id=XfmSMPTe2tg}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|title=1985 USA vs Argentina ABC presents \"USA vs The World\"|id=Aq1y44tu9Y4}}</ref> - Michaels initially joined ABC as the back-up announcer on ''[[Monday Night Baseball]]'' in 1976. The following year, he was promoted to the network on a full-time basis. He became the lead announcer, replacing Keith Jackson in 1983. Over the next three decades, Michaels covered a wide variety of sports for ABC, including [[Major League Baseball on ABC|Major League Baseball]], [[College Football on ABC|college football]], [[College Basketball on ABC|college basketball]], [[ice hockey]], track and field events, [[horse racing]], [[PGA Tour on ABC|golf]], [[boxing]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Katz|first=Michael|date=May 14, 1985|title=TV SPORTS;   RATING BOXING PEOPLE AND THEIR SHOWS|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/05/14/sports/tv-sports-rating-boxing-people-and-their-shows.html|work=The New York Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref> (such as the 1985 [[Marvin Hagler vs. Thomas Hearns|Marvin Hagler/Thomas Hearns fight]]), [[figure skating]], [[road cycling]], and many events of the [[Olympics on ABC|Olympic Games]] as well as the Olympic trials.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/abcsports/mnf/s/2003/0211/1507336.html|date=May 13, 2003|accessdate=August 14, 2009|title=Michaels signs contract extension with ABC|work=ABC Sports online|publisher=ABCSports.com}}</ref>\n\n*[[Jerry Quarry]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dmboxing.com/my-memory-of-jerry-quarry/|title=My Memory of Jerry Quarry|last=Farris|first=Rick |date=May 28, 2011|website=dmboxing.com|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>\n\n*[[Chris Schenkel]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Chris Schenkel Career Retrospective|id=m5JxYNJEyIc}}</ref> - [[ABC Sports]] hired Schenkel in 1965, and there he broadcast [[college football]], [[Major League Baseball]], [[National Basketball Association|NBA basketball]], [[golf]] and [[tennis]] tournaments, boxing, [[auto racing]], and the Summer and Winter [[Olympic Games]]. \n\n*[[Al Trautwig]]\n\n*[[Alex Wallau]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://basementgymboxing.blogspot.com/2015/05/alex-wallau-on-young-mike-tyson-his-era.html|title=Alex Wallau On Young Mike Tyson & His Era: Quote Spotlight|last= |first= |date=May 20, 2015|website=Basement Gym Boxing|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Bernstein|first=Al|date= |title=Al Bernstein: 30 Years, 30 Undeniable Truths About Boxing, Sports, and TV|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ii25qWpcEMcC&pg=PT166&lpg=PT166&dq=al+bernstein+abc&source=bl&ots=mfzePO6xuD&sig=ACfU3U1R7E9bzxo32wEn2QjGQ64NAlbY5w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjx9rHqkozkAhVSQq0KHcEeCFcQ6AEwDXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=al%20bernstein%20abc&f=false|location= |publisher= Diversion Books|page= |isbn= |author-link=}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|title=Boxing - 1985 - Jim Lampley + Alex Wallau Interview + Highlights Of Mark Breland Vs Darryl Anthony|id=_pxzijlhsOY}}</ref> - He worked primarily on ABC's boxing coverage with announcer [[Howard Cosell]]. In 1986, after Cosell's retirement, Wallau became ABC's [[boxing]] analyst.  He was honored by the [[Boxing Writers Association of America]] as the top television boxing journalist in his first year.\n\n=====[[Howard Cosell]]=====\nCosell rose to prominence in the early 1960s, covering boxer [[Muhammad Ali]], beginning from the time he fought under his [[Name at birth|birth name]], Cassius Clay. The two seemed to have an affinity despite their different personalities, and complemented each other in broadcasts. Cosell was one of the first sportscasters to refer to the boxer as Muhammad Ali after he changed his name, and supported him when he refused to be inducted into the military. Cosell called most of Ali's fights immediately before and after the boxer returned from his three-year exile in October 1970. Those fights were broadcast on taped delay usually a week after they were transmitted on closed circuit. However, Cosell did not call two of Ali's biggest fights, the [[Rumble in the Jungle]] in October 1974 and the first [[Fight of the Century|Ali\u2013Joe Frazier bout]] in March 1971. Promoter [[Jerry Perenchio]] selected actor [[Burt Lancaster]], who had never provided color commentary for a fight, to work the bout with longtime announcer [[Don Dunphy]] and former light-heavyweight champion [[Archie Moore]]. Cosell attended that fight as a spectator only. He would do a voiceover of that bout, when it was shown on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] a few days before the second [[Muhammad Ali vs. Joe Frazier II|Ali-Frazier bout]] in January 1974.\n\nPerhaps his most famous call took place in the [[George Foreman#The Sunshine Showdown vs. Joe Frazier|fight]] between [[Joe Frazier]] and [[George Foreman]] for the World Heavyweight Championship in [[Kingston, Jamaica]] in 1973. When Foreman knocked Frazier to the mat the first of six times, roughly two minutes into the first round, Cosell yelled out:\n\n{{quote|Down Goes Frazier! Down Goes Frazier! Down Goes Frazier!}}\n\nHis call of Frazier's first trip to the mat became one of the most quoted phrases in American sports broadcasting history. Foreman beat Frazier by a TKO in the second round to win the [[World heavyweight boxing championship|World Heavyweight Championship]].\n\nCosell provided blow-by-blow commentary for ABC of some of boxing's biggest matches during the 1970s and the early 1980s, including [[Ken Norton]]'s upset win over Ali in 1973 and Ali's defeat of [[Leon Spinks]] in 1978 recapturing the Heavyweight title for the third time. His signature [[toupee]] was unceremoniously knocked off in front of live ABC cameras when a scuffle broke out after a broadcast match between [[Scott LeDoux]] and Johnny Boudreaux. Cosell quickly retrieved his hairpiece and replaced it. During interviews in studio with Ali, the champion would tease and threaten to remove the hairpiece with Cosell playing along but never allowing it to be touched. On one of these occasions, Ali quipped, \"Cosell, you're a phony, and that thing on your head comes from the tail of a pony.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5294873|title=Ali and Cosell, Irresistible Enigmas}}</ref>\n\nWith typical headline generating drama, Cosell abruptly ended his broadcast association with the sport of boxing while providing coverage for ABC for the heavyweight championship bout between [[Larry Holmes]] and [[Randall \"Tex\" Cobb]] on November 26, 1982<ref>{{cite book |last=Bloom |first=John|date= |title=There You Have it: The Life, Legacy, and Legend of Howard Cosell|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pRirlKfG3J0C&pg=PA153&dq=ABC+Sports+Boxing&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjOhp6EkozkAhULEawKHYzfBE44KBDoATACegQIBBAC#v=onepage&q=ABC%20Sports%20Boxing&f=false|location= |publisher=Univ of Massachusetts Press|page=153|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref>. Halfway through the bout and with Cobb absorbing a beating, Cosell stopped providing anything more than rudimentary comments about round number and the participants punctuated with occasional declarations of disgust during the 15 rounds. He declared shortly after the fight to a national television audience that he had broadcast his last professional boxing match.\n\nIn the [[Boxing at the 1976 Summer Olympics|1976 Summer Games in Montreal]], and the [[Boxing at the 1984 Summer Olympics|1984 games in Los Angeles]], Cosell was the main voice for boxing. [[Sugar Ray Leonard]] won the gold medal in his light welterweight class at Montreal, beginning his meteoric rise to a world professional title a few years later, and Cosell became close to Leonard, during this period, announcing many of his fights.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">\"I Never Played The Game\", by Howard Cosell, 1985</ref>\n\n===Cancelled 2007 card===\n{{see also|Boxing on ESPN}}\n\nSeven years after ABC's last boxing card, they were scheduled to broadcast a card from [[Boardwalk Hall]] in [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]] on April 22, 2007. The card would've featured former light heavyweight champion [[Antonio Tarver]] facing off against [[Elvir Muriqi]]. Promoter Joe DeGuardia of Star Boxing had been working on the [[Brokered programming|time buy]] deal (in other words, DeGuardia was not paid a licensing fee by ABC, but rather bought an hour of time from the network). The production would've been handled by ABC's sister company, [[ESPN]] with ''[[Friday Night Fights]]'' commentators [[Joe Tessitore]] and [[Teddy Atlas]]. The bout was ultimately scrapped<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tss.ib.tv/boxing/articles-of-2007/5142-antonio-tarver-master-of-second-chances|title=Antonio Tarver: Master Of Second Chances|last=Keenan|first=Ronan|date=June 4, 2007|website=The Sweet Science|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> amid rumors that Tarver would not be able to make the 175 pound weight limit.\n\n===''Premier Boxing Champions'' (2015)===\nOn March 19, 2015, ESPN announced that ''Friday Night Fights'' would air for the final time on May 22, 2015, covering the finals of the 2015 Boxcino tournament. The network announced that it had reached a multi-year deal with [[Al Haymon]]'s ''[[Premier Boxing Champions]]'' to broadcast 11 events per-year on the main ESPN network, primarily on Saturday nights, and an afternoon event on [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]]. [[Joe Tessitore]] and [[Teddy Atlas]] were carried over to serve as hosts. ESPN is one of several major broadcasters that airs fights through the promotion, which also includes [[NBC]], [[CBS]], their respective cable sports networks, as well as [[Spike (TV network)|Spike]].<ref name=deadline-pbcespn>{{cite web|title=ESPN Joins Premier Boxing Champions\u2019 Corner, Knocking Out \u2018Friday Night Fights\u2019|url=https://deadline.com/2015/03/espn-premier-boxing-champions-friday-night-fights-ending-1201394575/|website=[Deadline.com|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|accessdate=March 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*''[[ABC Wide World of Sports Boxing]]''\n*[[Boxing on the radio]]\n*[[Olympics_on_ABC_commentators#Summer_Olympics]]\n*[[The Super Fight]] - Debates subsequently took place over the next three decades as to whether at least one print of film had survived. It was cited that many theaters had continued to play the film long after January 20, 1970, and was also noted that the film had one airing on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Wide World of Sports (US TV series)|Wide World of Sports]]'' in 1970, and another on [[CBS]] late night in 1977, with many more broadcasts alleged throughout.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.espn.com/abcsports/wwos/highlights/boxing.html Wide World Boxing Milestones and Highlights]\n**[http://espn.go.com/abcsports/wwos/milestones/1960s.html ''Wide World of Sports'' Highlights -- 1960s]\n**[http://espn.go.com/abcsports/wwos/milestones/1970s.html ''Wide World of Sports'' Highlights -- 1970s]\n**[http://espn.go.com/abcsports/wwos/milestones/1980s.html ''Wide World of Sports'' Highlights -- 1980s]\n**[http://espn.go.com/abcsports/wwos/milestones/1990s.html ''Wide World of Sports'' Highlights -- 1990s]\n**[http://imasportsphile.com/category/wide-world-of-sports/ Wide World of Sports \u2013 ImaSportsphile]\n*[https://abcnews.go.com/search?searchtext=Boxing ABC News - Boxing]\n*[http://www.skypoint.com/members/schutz19/boxing.htm BOXING ON TV]\n\n{{ESPN on ABC}}\n{{ABC's Wide World of Sports}}\n{{Boxing on television}}\n{{Boxing on ABC}}\n\n[[Category:Wide World of Sports (American TV series)]]\n[[Category:ABC Sports]]\n[[Category:Boxing television series|ABC]]\n[[Category:American Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:1940s American television series]]\n[[Category:1950s American television series]]\n[[Category:1960s American television series]]\n[[Category:1970s American television series]]\n[[Category:1980s American television series]]\n[[Category:1990s American television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American television series]]\n[[Category:1949 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2000 American television series endings]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n|show_name            = ''Boxing on ABC''\n|image                = \n|caption              = \n|show_name_2          = \n|genre                = [[Professional boxing]] bouts\n|creator              = \n|developer            = \n|director             = \n|starring             = {{ubl|[[Don Chevrier]]|[[Howard Cosell]]|[[Dan Dierdorf]]|[[Keith Jackson]]|[[Jim Lampley]]|[[Al Michaels]]|[[Jerry Quarry]]|[[Chris Schenkel]]|[[Al Trautwig]]|[[Alex Wallau]]}}\n|theme_music_composer = \n|opentheme            = \n|endtheme             =\n|composer             = \n|country              = [[United States]]\n|language             = [[English language|English]]\n|num_seasons          = \n|num_episodes         = \n|list_episodes        = \n|executive_producer   = \n|producer             = \n|location             = \n|camera               = [[Multi-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n|runtime              = Various\n|company              = [[ESPN on ABC|ABC Sports]]\n|distributor          = \n|channel              = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n|picture_format       = [[Color]]\n|first_aired          = {{Start date|1964|11|11}}\n|last_aired           = {{End date|2000|6|17}}\n|preceded_by          = \n|followed_by          = \n|related              = ''[[Wide World of Sports (American TV program)|Wide World of Sports]]''\n|website              = https://abcnews.go.com/search?searchtext=Boxing\n}}\n\n'''''Boxing on ABC''''' refers to a series of [[boxing]] events<ref>{{cite book |last=Rapak|first=Dan|date= |title=Brought to You by . . .|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dH40Fl8vG2IC&pg=PA363&dq=ABC+Sports+Boxing&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi24Y3qk4zkAhVQgK0KHVWDCyc4WhDoATAFegQIAxAC#v=onepage&q=ABC%20Sports%20Boxing&f=false|location= |publisher=AuthorHouse|page=363|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref> that have been televised on the [[American Broadcasting Company]]. Many of these events aired under the ''[[Wide World of Sports (American TV series)|Wide World of Sports]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boxrec.com/media/index.php/ABC's_Wide_World_of_Sports_Televised_Fights|title=ABC's Wide World of Sports Televised Fights|last= |first= |date= |website=BoxRec.com|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> banner which began on April 11, 1964 when challenger [[Muhammad Ali]], then known as Cassius Clay, [[Muhammad Ali vs. Sonny Liston|defeated]] champion [[Sonny Liston]] in the seventh round. ABC's final boxing card occurred on June 17, 2000<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxingscene.com/antonio-tarver-speaks-on-fight-postponement--8193|title=Antonio Tarver Speaks on Fight Postponement|last=Vester|first=Mark|date=April 13, 2007|website=BoxingScene.com|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|title=Jose Luis Castillo vs Stevie Johnston - 1/3|id=7zQaFh9QhQM&t}}</ref>.\n\n==History==\n===''Tomorrow's Boxing Champions'' (1949-50)===\nThe first incarnation of boxing telecasts on ABC was ''Tomorrow's Boxing Champions'', which aired on Tuesday nights beginning in January 1949. Originating from [[Chicago]], the program featured young, unranked fighters. [[Bob Elson]] did the blow-by-blow commentary. The series concluded in September 1950.\n\n===''Meet the Champ'' (1952)===\nIn January 1952, ABC premiered ''Meet the Champ'', which was a collection of bouts involving members of the [[United States Armed Forces|armed forces]]. The program aired on Thursday nights, with Wally Butterfield announcing.\n\n===''Saturday Night Fights'' (1953-55)===\nIn 1953, [[Ray Arcel]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Kriegel|first=Mark|date= |title=The Good Son: The Life of Ray \"Boom Boom\" Mancini|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yzN94ZdYV8oC&pg=PA90&dq=ABC+Sports+Boxing&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi24Y3qk4zkAhVQgK0KHVWDCyc4WhDoATAJegQIBxAC#v=onepage&q=ABC%20Sports%20Boxing&f=false|location= |publisher=Simon and Schuster|page=90|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref> began promoting bouts on ABC. Unfortunately, shortly after arranging the fights for ABC<ref>{{cite book |last=Dewey|first=Donald|date= |title=Ray Arcel: A Boxing Biography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GQsHqHfqcq4C&pg=PA152&lpg=PA152&dq=ray+arcel+abc&source=bl&ots=wfsRPRj1Ps&sig=ACfU3U1Y2NmSWL-iMC_Iv8mFufBI5u4zRw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjeqt-nlozkAhVIgK0KHYcUAyo4ChDoATAAegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=ray%20arcel%20abc&f=false|location= |publisher=McFarland|page=152|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref>, Arcel<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibhof.com/pages/about/inductees/nonparticipant/arcel.html|title=Ray Arcel |last= |first= |date= |website=International Boxing Hall of Fame|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> ran afoul of organized crime. The matches on ABC competed with other network television fights run by the [[International Boxing Club]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxing.com/ray_arcel_the_dean_of_them_all.html|title=Ray Arcel: Dean of Them All|last=Ecksel|first=Robert|date=January 8, 2013 |website=Boxing.com|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> (IBC), who were reputed to have underworld ties.\n\n[[Bill Stern]] did blow-by-blow commentary when ''Saturday Night Fights'' premiered. Come the fall, Jack Gregson took over from Stern.\n\n===''Boxing from Ridgewood Grove'' and ''Motor City Boxing'' (1953)===\nIn February 1953, ABC premiered ''Boxing from Ridgewood Grove''. It aired on Tuesdays nights, with [[Jason Owen]] as the announcer in the first month and Bob Finnegan taking over until its cancellation in August. In March 1953, ABC brought ''Motor City Boxing'' from [[Detroit]]. The program would air for three months of Thursdays, with Don Wattrick at the providing commentary.\n\n===''Boxing from Eastern Parkway'' (1954)===\nIn May 1954, ''[[Boxing from Eastern Parkway]]'' moved from the [[DuMont Television Network]] to ABC. Tommy Logran handled the blow-by-blow commentary while occasionally being helped by Bob Finnegan and Fred Sayles. The series ended when ABC failed to renew its contract with the arena after picking up the rights to show fights at the [[International Boxing Club]].<ref name=\"BrooksMarsh2009\">{{cite book|author1=Tim Brooks|author2=Earle F. Marsh|title=The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network and Cable TV Shows, 1946-Present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w8KztFy6QYwC&pg=PA174|date=24 June 2009|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-48320-1|page=174}}</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5wQsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=esYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1251%2C4906110 \"Eastern Parkway Finished\"], [[Associated Press]] in ''[[TimesDaily]]'', May 17, 1955.</ref>\n\n===''The Wednesday Night Fights'' (1955-60)===\nAfter cancellation of ''[[Pabst Blue Ribbon Bouts]]'' on CBS in 1955, the series was picked up by ABC, renamed ''The Wednesday Night Fights'',<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w8KztFy6QYwC&lpg=PA174&pg=PA174|title=The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network and Cable TV Shows, 1946-Present|last=Brooks|first=Tim|last2=Marsh|first2=Earle F.|date=2009-06-24|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=9780307483201|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Mee|first=Bob|date= |title=Ali and Liston: The Boy Who Would Be King and the Ugly Bear|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PUAS56Z-51EC&pg=PA45&dq=Boxing+on+ABC&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjOxO_ojI7kAhVSL6wKHSChAqk4bhDoATAJegQIABAC#v=onepage&q=Boxing%20on%20ABC&f=false|location= |publisher=Skyhorse Publishing Inc.|page=45|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref> and continued until 1960.\n\n[[Russ Hodges]] and [[Jack Drees]] both stayed with the show when it transferred from CBS. Hodges however, left in October 1955 and Drees was the only regular announcer for the five years it stayed on ABC.\n\n===''Fight of the Week'' (1960-63)===\nAfter [[NBC]]-TV's cancellation of ''[[Gillette Cavalcade of Sports|The Gillette Cavalcade of Sports]]'' in the spring of [[1960 in television|1960]], ABC took over the [[prime time]] boxing program, although it was renamed ''[[Fight of the Week]]''. Legendary boxing commentator [[Don Dunphy]] did the blow-by-blow description of the bouts, which took place on Saturday beginning in October 1960 and running through September 1963. \n\nFrom there, the series moved to Friday nights, where it continued until ABC finally canceled prime time boxing after the bout of September 11, 1964, permanently ending 18 years of regularly scheduled prime time boxing on [[United States|U.S.]] broadcast network television. One reason for the downturn of televised boxing occurred on ''Fight of the Week'''s [[Benny Paret vs. Emile Griffith III|the March 24, 1962 broadcast]], when [[Emile Griffith]] defeated [[Benny Paret|Benny \"The Kid\" Paret]] for the Welterweight Championship at [[New York City|New York]]'s [[Madison Square Garden]]. Paret was carried from the ring unconscious, and died several days later as a result of his injuries that he had sustained in that bout.\n\n===''Wide World of Sports'' (1964-2000)===\nPrior to the advent of ''Wide World of Sports'', many major [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|heavyweight boxing title]] matches were televised via \u201c[[Closed-circuit television|closed-circuit]]\u201d (this generally meant that you had go to a movie theater to see it, pay a decent-sized amount of money to get it, and then watch it on a giant screen). Often, ''Wide World of Sports'' would show full-length replays of the fights a week or two later; these replays were usually called by [[Howard Cosell]], who became one of the best-known (and possibly most controversial) sportscaster in American television history.\n\n[[Jerry Quarry]] retired for over two and a half years after his 1975 fight with [[Ken Norton]] fight. At around this time, Quarry signed a contract with ABC to be a boxing commentator. Quarry was very popular in this position, drawing the ire of Howard Cosell, an ABC commentator being pushed out of some work by Quarry. In mid-1977, a return match was being put together which would put Quarry in against a ranked heavyweight. The ranked heavyweight would be Italian Lorenzo Zanon. The match was to be televised on ABC, where Quarry was contracted. But both fighters signed to have the bout televised on [[Boxing on CBS|CBS]]. When Quarry, who often negotiated his own fight contracts, signed the bout to CBS, he lost his ABC contract. \n\nIn 1976, ABC made a deal with promoter [[Don King (boxing promoter)|Don King]] and [[The Ring (magazine)|''The Ring'' magazine]] to stage a tournament<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.si.com/more-sports/2014/10/31/al-michaels-howard-cosell-you-cant-make-excerpt|title=Book excerpt: Al Michaels reflects on his time with Howard Cosell|last=Michaels, Wertheim|first=Al, L. Jon|date=October 31, 2014|website=Sports Illustrated|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> to determine the best fighter from the U.S. in each weight division. The tournament, dubbed the United States Boxing Championships was scheduled to begin on January 16, 1977 with ABC agreeing to finance the tournament with an investment of between $1.5 million and $2 million<ref>\n{{cite book |last=Heller|first=Peter|date= |title=Bad Intentions: The Mike Tyson Story|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zQeJ5T9cGoAC&pg=PA211&dq=1977+ring+magazine+abc+don+king&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjI05eKk47kAhVHSq0KHQZSBFUQ6AEwBHoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=1977%20ring%20magazine%20abc%20don%20king&f=false|location= |publisher=Da Capo Press, Incorporated|page=211|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref>. Soon however, it determined that King was essentially using the tournament to sign the best fighters to exclusive contracts. To make matters worse, ''The Ring'' was falsifying records and inflating rankings as a means of getting a number of fighters into the tournament for King.\n\n[[Sugar Ray Leonard]]'s bout with [[Wilfred Ben\u00edtez]] on November 30, 1979<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thefightcity.com/benitez-vs-leonard/|title=Nov. 30, 1979: Benitez vs Leonard -- Sugar Ray Wins|last= Portis|first=Robert|date=November 30, 2018|website=The Fight City|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> marked the first time in the era of big-money sports events that a non-heavyweight fight would be carried as the main event on [[prime time]] television<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.si.com/vault/1979/11/26/824205/sugar-sure-is-sweet-in-driving-toward-a-welterweight-title-shot-ray-leonard-has-evoked-another-sugar-ray-and-that-venerable-leonard-benny|title=SUGAR SURE IS SWEET|last=Mack|first=William|date=November 26, 1979|website=Sports Illustrated|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxinginsider.com/columns/boxing-on-primetime-network-tv-when-boxing-really-hit-paydirt/|title=Boxing on Primetime Network TV? When Boxing Really Hit Paydirt|last=Charles|first=Jay|date=January 23, 2013|website=Boxing Insider|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>.\n\nOn November 15, 1984, ABC broadcast 'A Night of Gold', a card from promoter [[Dan Duva]]'s 'Main Events'<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2014/11/14/7173919/olympic-article-part-2|title=Boxing History: 30th Anniversary of 'A Night of Gold' Part One|last=McLachlan|first=Kyle|date=November 14, 2014|website=Bad Left Hook|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>, featuring no less than four gold medal winners ([[Mark Breland]], [[Tyrell Biggs]], [[Pernell Whitaker]] and [[Meldrick Taylor]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Katz|first=Michael|date=November 15, 1984|title=HOLYFIELD FUTURE IS IN HIS HANDS|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/11/15/sports/holyfield-future-is-in-his-hands.html|work=The New York Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref>) from that year's [[Boxing at the 1984 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympic games]], as well as those lagging behind in the runners-up spots.\n\nIn 1992, ABC announced plans to counterprogram<ref>{{cite news |last=Williams|first=Jennifer|date=February 7, 1992|title=CBS ANNOUNCERS ARE READY FOR OLYMPICS|url=https://www.dailypress.com/news/dp-xpm-19920207-1992-02-07-9202070180-story.html|work=Daily Press|location= |access-date= }}</ref> the [[1992 Winter Olympics|Winter Olympics]] on [[CBS Olympic broadcasts|CBS]] with boxing, a sport at that point, seldom seen on network television. This particular boxing series was sponsored by [[Fruit of the Loom]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart|first=Larry|date=February 7, 1992 |title=No Need to Coach Fratello for TV|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1992-02-07-sp-1329-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Nidetz|first=Steve|date=January 6, 1992|title=ABC SAW NO DOLLAR SENSE IN OLYMPICS|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1992-01-06-9201020585-story.html|work=Chicago Tribune|location= |access-date= }}</ref>. ABC proceeded to forgo the typical [[United States dollar|$]]300,000 rights fees of the prior year, and instead, set a $75,000 limit and scheduled three consecutive Saturdays of action<ref>{{cite news |last=Craig|first=Jack|date=February 16, 1992|title=Some, networks included, see fight game gaining from Tyson's loss|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/bs-xpm-1992-02-16-1992047146-story.html|work=The Baltimore Sun|location= |access-date= }}</ref>.\n\n====Notable bouts====\n{{main|List of events broadcast on Wide World of Sports (American TV series)}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|'''Year'''\n|'''Day'''\n|'''Event'''\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1964\n|April 11\n|Challenger [[Cassius Clay]], soon to adopt the [[Muslim]] name of Muhammad Ali, knocks out champion [[Sonny Liston]] in the [[Muhammad Ali versus Sonny Liston#The first fight|seventh round]] in [[Miami Beach, Florida]].\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Sonny Liston}}\n|-\n|May 30\n|[[U.S. Olympic Boxing Trials]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=1988 U S Olympic Boxing Trials|id=ZwKBU57C58g}}</ref>. \n|-\n|1965\n|May 29\n|The [[Muhammad Ali versus Sonny Liston#The second bout|rematch]] between [[Muhammad Ali]] and [[Sonny Liston]] from [[Lewiston, Maine]].\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|1966\n|April 2\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] defeats [[George Chuvalo]] in a 15-round decision to retain his [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] in [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], Canada.\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. George Chuvalo}}\n|-\n|May 21\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] retains his [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] title with a sixth-round TKO of [[Henry Cooper]] in London.\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Henry Cooper}}\n|-\n|September 10\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] defeats [[Karl Mildenberger]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Muhammad Ali vs Karl Mildenberger 1966-09-10|id=u0bbw5J4fjU}}</ref> in a [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|heavyweight title]] defense, live from [[Frankfurt]], [[West Germany]] with a 12th-round TKO.\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Karl Mildenberger}}\n|-\n|November 26\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] defends his [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|world heavyweight title]] for the sixth time in 1966 on ''Wide World of Sports'' against [[Cleveland Williams]].\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Cleveland Williams}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1967\n|February 11\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] defends his [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] against [[Ernie Terrell]] in [[Houston]], [[Texas]].\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Ernie Terrell}}\n|-\n|March 11\n|Interview with [[Muhammad Ali]] and [[Wilt Chamberlain]].\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1970\n|February 21\n|[[Joe Frazier]] knocks out [[Jimmy Ellis (boxer)|Jimmy Ellis]] in the fifth round for the vacant [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] from New York City.\n|-\n|October 31\n|In [[Atlanta]], [[Muhammad Ali]] defeats [[Jerry Quarry]] in the third round, in his first fight in three years.\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Jerry Quarry}}\n|-\n|November 21\n|[[Joe Frazier]] knocks out [[Bob Foster (boxer)|Bob Foster]] in the second round of their [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] fight in [[Detroit]].\n|-\n|1971\n|March 13\n|Analysis of the [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] [[Fight of the Century|fight]] between [[Muhammad Ali]] and [[Joe Frazier]] with Muhammad Ali. \n{{main|Fight of the Century}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1972\n|September 23\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] ends the career of former [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|world heavyweight champion]] [[Floyd Patterson]] with a seventh-round knockout in New York City.\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Floyd Patterson}}\n|-\n|November 25\n|[[Muhammad Ali]]-[[Bob Foster (boxer)|Bob Foster]] fight.\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Bob Foster}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1973\n|January 27\n|[[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] fight between [[Joe Frazier]] and [[George Foreman]] from [[Kingston, Jamaica]].\n{{main|Joe Frazier vs. George Foreman}}\n|-\n|March 31\n|[[Ken Norton]] wins a 12-round decision against [[Muhammad Ali]] in their heavyweight fight from [[San Diego]], [[California]].\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Ken Norton}}\n|-\n|September 15\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] wins his rematch with [[Ken Norton]] rematch in 12 rounds.\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|1974\n|January 26\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] and [[Joe Frazier]] scuffle<ref>{{cite book |last=Hudson Jr.|first=David L.|date= |title=Boxing in America: An Autopsy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VcKGH5Oju1gC&pg=PA70&dq=Boxing+on+ABC+Sports&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiQuuLYj47kAhVRmK0KHYvbDpkQ6AEwB3oECAcQAg#v=onepage&q=Boxing%20on%20ABC%20Sports&f=false|location= |publisher= ABC-CLIO|page=70|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|title=ABC Wide World of Sports - Ali Frazier Studio Brawl|id=2Dh72Os_97c}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|title=Muhammad Ali and Joe Frazier Wide World Of Sports Studio Brawl 1974|id=0-u_Q3eVYU0}}</ref> during the telecast as they watch tape of their [[Fight of the Century|first fight]] in 1971.\n|- \n|March 2\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] defeats [[Joe Frazier]] in their [[Ali-Frazier II|second fight]] in New York City.\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Joe Frazier II}}\n|-\n|March 16\n|[[Roberto Dur\u00e1n]] knocks out [[Esteban De Jes\u00fas]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Roberto Duran vs Esteban De Jesus II|id=0K3nJBxwttk}}</ref> in the 11th round to retain his [[List of lightweight boxing champions|World Lightweight championship]] from [[Panama City]], [[Panama]].\n|-\n|March 31\n|[[George Foreman]] scores a second-round TKO of [[Ken Norton]] in a [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] fight.\n{{main|George Foreman vs. Ken Norton}}\n|-\n|September 21\n|''Wide World of Sports'' returns to [[Havana]], [[Cuba]] for the [[1974 World Amateur Boxing Championships|World Boxing Championships]], which featured [[Te\u00f3filo Stevenson]].\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|1975\n|January 5\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] knocks out [[George Foreman]] in the [[The Rumble in the Jungle|eighth round]] to reclaim the [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight]] title from [[Kinshasa]], [[Zaire]].\n{{main|The Rumble in the Jungle}}\n|-\n|March 29\n|[[Muhammad Ali]] scores a 15th-round TKO of [[Chuck Wepner]] in their [[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] fight.\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Chuck Wepner}}\n|-\n|July 26\n|Coverage of the [[North American Continental Boxing Championships]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=1985 North American Boxing Championship|id=_eq1I7BYcWI}}</ref>. \n|-\n|September 13\n|[[List of heavyweight boxing champions|World Heavyweight Championship]] fight between [[Muhammad Ali]] and [[Joe Bugner]] from [[Kuala Lampur]], [[Malaysia]].\n{{main|Muhammad Ali vs. Joe Bugner}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1976<ref>{{cite book |last=Newfield|first=Jack|date= |title=The Life and Crimes of Don King: The Shame of Boxing in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sWYN6cETROQC&pg=PA105&dq=ABC+Sports+Boxing&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjI477bkIzkAhUB0KwKHbMNB2kQ6AEwBnoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=ABC%20Sports%20Boxing&f=false|location= |publisher= UNET 2 Corporation|page=105|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref>\n|January 11\n|''Wide World of Sports'' telecasts tape of [[Muhammad Ali]] defeating [[Joe Frazier]] in the \"[[Thrilla in Manila|Thriller in Manilla]]\" heavyweight title fight. \n{{main|Thrilla in Manila}}\n|-\n|October 2\n|Exclusive ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' still photographs of the Muhammad Ali-Ken Norton heavyweight fight and interviews with [[Ken Norton]], [[Joe Frazier]] and [[George Foreman]].\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1977\n|January 2\n|Interview with [[Muhammad Ali]].\n|-\n|May 14\n|[[Sugar Ray Leonard]] defeats [[Willie Rodriguez]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Sugar Ray Leonard vs Willie Rodriguez.avi|id=_zf1v4yIYKs}}</ref> in the second fight of his professional career. \n|-\n|1978\n|February 12\n|USA-Cuba Amateur boxing marks the first live telecast from Cuba since [[Fidel Castro|Castro]] came to power in 1959.\n|-\n|1979\n|February 4\n|[[Alexis Arg\u00fcello]] and [[Alfredo Escalera]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=The Bloody Battle Of Bayamon: Alexis Arguello vs Alfredo Escalera|id=8ipr2Ev3wa8}}</ref> for the [[List of WBC world champions#Super featherweight|WBC Super Featherweight]] title. Arguello retained his title with a 13th-round knockout.\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1980\n|July 19\n|[[Sugar Ray Leonard]] and [[Roberto Dur\u00e1n]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Roberto Duran vs Sugar Ray Leonard/ ABC Wide World Of Sports Leonard vs Duran w:Cosell|id=guTzuum-h40}}</ref> fight for the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] [[List of welterweight boxing champions|Welterweight Championship]].\n{{main|Sugar Ray Leonard vs. Roberto Dur\u00e1n II}}\n|-\n|September 27\n|In his second bid for the [[World Boxing Association|WBA]]/[[World Boxing Council|WBC]] [[List of middleweight boxing champions|Middleweight championship]], [[Marvelous Marvin Hagler]] scores a third-round TKO of [[Alan Minter]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Marvin Hagler -vs- Alan Minter 10/6/80|id=CfcxEHcP-Zw}}</ref> in a fight marred by a crowd riot.\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1981\n|September 5\n|[[Salvador S\u00e1nchez]] retains his [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] [[List of featherweight boxing champions|Featherweight Championship]] with a victory over [[Wilfredo G\u00f3mez]]. \n|-\n|October 17\n|[[Sugar Ray Leonard]] scores a 14th-round TKO of [[Thomas Hearns]] in a [[World Boxing Council|WBC]]/[[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[List of welterweight boxing champions|Welterweight Championship]] [[Sugar Ray Leonard vs. Thomas Hearns|fight]].\n{{main|Sugar Ray Leonard vs. Thomas Hearns}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1982\n|November 27\n|[[Te\u00f3filo Stevenson]] fights [[Tyrell Biggs]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Teofilo Stevenson {{!}} Tyrell Biggs I (a) 1/2|id=g_b9S4nZOe4}}</ref> from [[Reno, Nevada|Reno, Nev.]]\n|-\n|December 11\n|[[Rafael Lim\u00f3n|Bazooka Lim\u00f3n]] loses his [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] [[List of super featherweight boxing champions|Super Featherweight Championship]] to [[Bobby Chacon]] in a 15-round decision, while [[Wilfredo G\u00f3mez]] retained his WBC [[List of super bantamweight boxing champions|Super Bantamweight title]] against [[Lupe Pinto]].\n|-\n|1984\n|February 18\n|The USA-Cuba amateur boxing matches<ref>{{YouTube|title=USA vs Cuba ABC \u201cWide World of Sports\u201d 1984|id=4kZ1beq1RUo}}</ref> from [[Reno, Nevada|Reno]].\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|1985\n|January 5\n|Live coverage of [[Mark Breland]]'s second professional fight against [[Marlon Palmer]] in [[Atlantic City, New Jersey|Atlantic City, N.J.]].\n|-\n|January 20\n|Second professional fights of [[Pernell Whitaker]] (vs [[Danny Avery]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Pernell Whitaker {{!}} Danny Avery 1/2|id=fiTh7FYYDbo}}</ref>), [[Evander Holyfield]] (vs [[Eric Winbush]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Evander Holyfield vs Eric Winbush Full Fight (HD)|id=LsKQzxfgfBs}}</ref>) and [[Meldrick Taylor]] (vs [[Dwight Pratchett]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Meldrick Taylor (2nd pro fight) vs. Dwight Pratchett - 1/20/1985 = Boxing|id=QDWJYrqaX50}}</ref>), live, from [[Atlantic City, New Jersey|Atlantic City]].\n|-\n|April 20\n|The second professional fight of Olympic gold medalist [[Tyrell Biggs]].\n|-\n|June 8\n|[[Barry McGuigan]] defeats [[Eusebio Pedroza]] to claim the [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[List of welterweight boxing champions|Welterweight title]] in London.\n|-\n|September 28\n|[[Barry McGuigan]] defends his [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[List of welterweight boxing champions|Welterweight title]] against [[Bernard Taylor (boxer)|Bernard Taylor]] in [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]].\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|1986\n|February 15\n|[[Barry McGuigan]] defends his [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[List of welterweight boxing champions|Welterweight title]] against [[Danilo Cabreira]] in [[Dublin]], Ireland.\n|-\n|March 29\n|In a delayed broadcast, [[\"Marvelous\" Marvin Hagler]] knocks out [[John \"The Beast\" Mugabi]] in the 11th-round of their [[List of middleweight boxing champions|World Middleweight Championship]].\n|-\n|July 12\n|[[Evander Holyfield]] wins his first world title with a 15-round decision against [[Dwight Qawi]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Dwight Muhammad Qawi vs Evander Holyfield I|id=7_iYdUlCJ8&t}}</ref> for the [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[List of cruiserweight boxing champions|Junior Heavyweight]] crown live from [[Atlanta]].\n{{main|Dwight Muhammad Qawi vs. Evander Holyfield}}\n|-\n|July 26\n|[[Mike Tyson]] destroys [[Marvis Frazier]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Mike Tyson vs Marvis Frazier \u1d34\u1d30 - BEST QUALITY AVAILABLE|id=CRCVwsIokEw}}</ref> with a first-round knockout in their live heavyweight fight from [[Glens Falls, New York|Glens Falls, N.Y.]] In the same show, [[Barry McGuigan]] loses his [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[List of welterweight boxing champions|Welterweight]] crown in a 15-round decision to [[Steve Cruz (boxer)|Steve Cruz]] in [[Las Vegas Strip|Las Vegas]].\n{{main|Mike Tyson vs. Marvis Frazier}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1989\n|March 4\n|[[Virgil Hill]]-[[Bobby Czyz]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=VIRGIL HILL VS BOBBY CZYZ|id=V6yXrA6umME}}</ref> fight for the [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[List of light heavyweight boxing champions|Light Heavyweight Championship]] in [[Bismarck, North Dakota]].\n|-\n|April 1\n|[[Evander Holyfield]]-[[Michael Dokes]] heavyweight fight and a live studio interview with Holyfield.\n|-\n|June 24\n|[[Dennis Andries]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Hurley|first=Matthew|date= |title=Ringside Reflections|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NSH6AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA67&dq=Boxing+on+ABC&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjOxO_ojI7kAhVSL6wKHSChAqk4bhDoATAHegQIBhAC#v=onepage&q=Boxing%20on%20ABC&f=false|location= |publisher=|page=67|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref>-[[Jeff Harding (boxer)|Jeff Harding]] for the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] [[List of light heavyweight boxing champions|Light Heavyweight titles]].\n|-\n|1990\n|March 31\n|[[Meldrick Taylor]] fights [[Julio C\u00e9sar Ch\u00e1vez]] for the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]]/[[International Boxing Federation|IBF]] [[List of super lightweight boxing champions|Junior Welterweight/Super Lightweight]] titles.\n{{main|Julio C\u00e9sar Ch\u00e1vez vs. Meldrick Taylor}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1991\n|March 2\n|[[Riddick Bowe]] versus [[Tyrell Biggs]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Riddick Bowe vs Tyrell Biggs|id=ArLFL3o5rA0}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|title=Riddick Bowe vs Tyrell Biggs [1/3]|id=uCSR2LY34IU}}</ref>.\n{{main|Riddick Bowe vs. Michael Dokes}}\n|-\n|June 1\n|[[Mike Tyson]] scores a [[Knockout|TKO]] of [[Donovan Ruddock|Razor Ruddock]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=1991 03 18 Mike Tyson & Donovan Ruddock|id=sm2_7k9e7NE}}</ref> in a heavyweight fight, taped on March 18.\n{{main|Mike Tyson vs. Donovan Ruddock}}\n|-\n|1992\n|February 1\n|A special report on [[Mike Tyson]]'s trial and conviction of rape.\n|-\n|1993\n|March 6\n|[[Riddick Bowe]] knocks out [[Evander Holyfield]] in the 11th-round of their fight from [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]]. \n{{main|Evander Holyfield vs. Riddick Bowe}}\n|-\n|1995<ref>{{YouTube|title=1995 ABC WBO Boxing commercial|id=Ml7LGdWceA4}}</ref>\n|July 22\n|[[Mike Tyson]] retrospective: one month before his return to the ring.\n|-\n|1997\n|April 19\n|''Wide World'' airs network television's first women's professional boxing match. Former kickboxer [[Yvonne Trevino]] wins the [[Women's International Boxing Federation|WIBF]] Superflyweight championship live from [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]] in a first-round TKO over [[Brenda Rouse]]. \n|-\n|2000\n|June 17\n|[[Jos\u00e9 Luis Castillo]] upsets [[Stevie Johnston]] in the lightweight championship bout in [[Bell Gardens, California]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/sports/boxing/columns/story?columnist=rafael_dan&id=2808676|title=Tarver fight on ABC might revive boxing on network TV|last=Rafael|first=Dan|date=March 23, 2007|website=ESPN.com|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>. \n|}\n\n====Commentators====\n{{see also|List_of_sports_announcers#Boxing|List of Wide World of Sports (American TV series) announcers}}\n\n*[[Don Chevrier]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Houston|first=William|date=December 18, 2007|title='Voice of God' silenced|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/voice-of-god-silenced/article20407174/|work=The Globe and Mail|location= |access-date= }} </ref>\n\n*[[Dan Dierdorf]] - In April 1987, Dierdorf was hired by [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] to join [[Al Michaels]] and [[Frank Gifford]] on ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' broadcasts.<ref name=Dream>{{cite news|title=Dierdorf Has Dream Come True|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|date=April 14, 1987|page=5B|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/6975835/dierdorf_has_dream_come_true/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> He spent 12 seasons on ''Monday Night Football'' before resigning the post in early 1999.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dierdorf leaves \"Monday Night Football\" team: Lack of progress on contract prompts St. Louisan to step down|author=Dan Caesar|newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|date=February 5, 1999|pages=D1, D7|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/6980135/dierdorf_leaves_monday_night_football/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> During his affiliation with ABC, Dierdorf also served as a blow-by-blow [[boxing]] commentator in 1989, beginning with [[Meldrick Taylor]]'s first defense of his championship, served as a correspondent for the network's coverage of the [[1988 Winter Olympics]] in [[Calgary]], and called play-by-play of some ''[[College Football on ABC]]'' games in the early 1990s.\n\n*[[Keith Jackson]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Boxing - 1985 - Keith Jackson Interviews Welterwt Mark Breland Before Hedgemon Robertson Fight|id=pm6erQ6FDPM}}</ref> - Though best known for his college football broadcasts, Jackson announced numerous other sports for ABC throughout his career, including [[Major League Baseball on ABC|Major League Baseball]], [[NBA on ABC|NBA basketball]], [[boxing]], [[auto racing]], [[PGA Tour on ABC|PGA Tour golf]], the [[United States Football League on ABC|USFL]], and the [[Olympics on ABC|Olympic Games]]. Jackson was a regular part of ABC's popular ''[[Wide World of Sports (US TV series)|Wide World of Sports]]'' (''WWOS''), covering both popular sports and obscure events like wrist wrestling. He also handled ''WWOS''' first coverage of boxer [[Sugar Ray Leonard]] at the North American Continental Boxing Championships on July 26, 1975, who Jackson called a young boxer to watch.<ref name=ABC70s>[http://espn.go.com/abcsports/wwos/milestones/1970s.html Wide World of Sports Highlights -- 1970s], ABC Sports Online, Accessed August 20, 2007.</ref> \n\n*[[Jim Lampley]]<ref>\n{{cite book |last=Early|first=Gerald|date= |title=The Cambridge Companion to Boxing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=axF9DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA304&dq=boxing+on+abc+wide+world+of+sports&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj74_COlo7kAhUG7qwKHd2tC2IQ6AEwAHoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=boxing%20on%20abc%20wide%20world%20of%20sports&f=false|location= |publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=304|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibhof.com/pages/about/inductees/observer/lampley.html|title=Jim Lampley|last= |first= |date= |website=International Boxing Hall of Fame|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|title=Boxing - ABC Review - Welterweight Title - Tomas Hearns VS Sugar Ray Leonard imasportsphile.com|id=521fBpPHmbk}}</ref> - In 1974, while in graduate school, he was chosen along with Don Tollefson in what [[ABC Sports|ABC]] called a ''talent hunt''. ABC executives thought that Lampley's youthful looks would make him endearing to the college crowds they looked to attract for their [[College Football on ABC|college football]] games. At ABC, he covered such events as [[Major League Baseball on ABC|Major League Baseball]] and [[College Basketball on ABC|college basketball]] games, the [[1986 Indianapolis 500|1986]] and [[1987 Indianapolis 500|1987]] [[Indianapolis 500]], the 1977 [[Monon Bell]] game between [[DePauw University]] and [[Wabash College]], five [[Olympics on ABC|Olympics]], as well as the program ''[[Wide World of Sports (US TV series)|Wide World of Sports]]''.\n\n*[[Al Michaels]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Stevie Johnston vs Jose Luis Castillo I|id=XfmSMPTe2tg}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|title=1985 USA vs Argentina ABC presents \"USA vs The World\"|id=Aq1y44tu9Y4}}</ref> - Michaels initially joined ABC as the back-up announcer on ''[[Monday Night Baseball]]'' in 1976. The following year, he was promoted to the network on a full-time basis. He became the lead announcer, replacing Keith Jackson in 1983. Over the next three decades, Michaels covered a wide variety of sports for ABC, including [[Major League Baseball on ABC|Major League Baseball]], [[College Football on ABC|college football]], [[College Basketball on ABC|college basketball]], [[ice hockey]], track and field events, [[horse racing]], [[PGA Tour on ABC|golf]], [[boxing]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Katz|first=Michael|date=May 14, 1985|title=TV SPORTS;   RATING BOXING PEOPLE AND THEIR SHOWS|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/05/14/sports/tv-sports-rating-boxing-people-and-their-shows.html|work=The New York Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref> (such as the 1985 [[Marvin Hagler vs. Thomas Hearns|Marvin Hagler/Thomas Hearns fight]]), [[figure skating]], [[road cycling]], and many events of the [[Olympics on ABC|Olympic Games]] as well as the Olympic trials.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/abcsports/mnf/s/2003/0211/1507336.html|date=May 13, 2003|accessdate=August 14, 2009|title=Michaels signs contract extension with ABC|work=ABC Sports online|publisher=ABCSports.com}}</ref>\n\n*[[Jerry Quarry]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dmboxing.com/my-memory-of-jerry-quarry/|title=My Memory of Jerry Quarry|last=Farris|first=Rick |date=May 28, 2011|website=dmboxing.com|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>\n\n*[[Chris Schenkel]]<ref>{{YouTube|title=Chris Schenkel Career Retrospective|id=m5JxYNJEyIc}}</ref> - [[ABC Sports]] hired Schenkel in 1965, and there he broadcast [[college football]], [[Major League Baseball]], [[National Basketball Association|NBA basketball]], [[golf]] and [[tennis]] tournaments, boxing, [[auto racing]], and the Summer and Winter [[Olympic Games]]. \n\n*[[Al Trautwig]]\n\n*[[Alex Wallau]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://basementgymboxing.blogspot.com/2015/05/alex-wallau-on-young-mike-tyson-his-era.html|title=Alex Wallau On Young Mike Tyson & His Era: Quote Spotlight|last= |first= |date=May 20, 2015|website=Basement Gym Boxing|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Bernstein|first=Al|date= |title=Al Bernstein: 30 Years, 30 Undeniable Truths About Boxing, Sports, and TV|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ii25qWpcEMcC&pg=PT166&lpg=PT166&dq=al+bernstein+abc&source=bl&ots=mfzePO6xuD&sig=ACfU3U1R7E9bzxo32wEn2QjGQ64NAlbY5w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjx9rHqkozkAhVSQq0KHcEeCFcQ6AEwDXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=al%20bernstein%20abc&f=false|location= |publisher= Diversion Books|page= |isbn= |author-link=}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|title=Boxing - 1985 - Jim Lampley + Alex Wallau Interview + Highlights Of Mark Breland Vs Darryl Anthony|id=_pxzijlhsOY}}</ref> - He worked primarily on ABC's boxing coverage with announcer [[Howard Cosell]]. In 1986, after Cosell's retirement, Wallau became ABC's [[boxing]] analyst.  He was honored by the [[Boxing Writers Association of America]] as the top television boxing journalist in his first year.\n\n=====[[Howard Cosell]]=====\nCosell rose to prominence in the early 1960s, covering boxer [[Muhammad Ali]], beginning from the time he fought under his [[Name at birth|birth name]], Cassius Clay. The two seemed to have an affinity despite their different personalities, and complemented each other in broadcasts. Cosell was one of the first sportscasters to refer to the boxer as Muhammad Ali after he changed his name, and supported him when he refused to be inducted into the military. Cosell called most of Ali's fights immediately before and after the boxer returned from his three-year exile in October 1970. Those fights were broadcast on taped delay usually a week after they were transmitted on closed circuit. However, Cosell did not call two of Ali's biggest fights, the [[Rumble in the Jungle]] in October 1974 and the first [[Fight of the Century|Ali\u2013Joe Frazier bout]] in March 1971. Promoter [[Jerry Perenchio]] selected actor [[Burt Lancaster]], who had never provided color commentary for a fight, to work the bout with longtime announcer [[Don Dunphy]] and former light-heavyweight champion [[Archie Moore]]. Cosell attended that fight as a spectator only. He would do a voiceover of that bout, when it was shown on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] a few days before the second [[Muhammad Ali vs. Joe Frazier II|Ali-Frazier bout]] in January 1974.\n\nPerhaps his most famous call took place in the [[George Foreman#The Sunshine Showdown vs. Joe Frazier|fight]] between [[Joe Frazier]] and [[George Foreman]] for the World Heavyweight Championship in [[Kingston, Jamaica]] in 1973. When Foreman knocked Frazier to the mat the first of six times, roughly two minutes into the first round, Cosell yelled out:\n\n{{quote|Down Goes Frazier! Down Goes Frazier! Down Goes Frazier!}}\n\nHis call of Frazier's first trip to the mat became one of the most quoted phrases in American sports broadcasting history. Foreman beat Frazier by a TKO in the second round to win the [[World heavyweight boxing championship|World Heavyweight Championship]].\n\nCosell provided blow-by-blow commentary for ABC of some of boxing's biggest matches during the 1970s and the early 1980s, including [[Ken Norton]]'s upset win over Ali in 1973 and Ali's defeat of [[Leon Spinks]] in 1978 recapturing the Heavyweight title for the third time. His signature [[toupee]] was unceremoniously knocked off in front of live ABC cameras when a scuffle broke out after a broadcast match between [[Scott LeDoux]] and Johnny Boudreaux. Cosell quickly retrieved his hairpiece and replaced it. During interviews in studio with Ali, the champion would tease and threaten to remove the hairpiece with Cosell playing along but never allowing it to be touched. On one of these occasions, Ali quipped, \"Cosell, you're a phony, and that thing on your head comes from the tail of a pony.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5294873|title=Ali and Cosell, Irresistible Enigmas}}</ref>\n\nWith typical headline generating drama, Cosell abruptly ended his broadcast association with the sport of boxing while providing coverage for ABC for the heavyweight championship bout between [[Larry Holmes]] and [[Randall \"Tex\" Cobb]] on November 26, 1982<ref>{{cite book |last=Bloom |first=John|date= |title=There You Have it: The Life, Legacy, and Legend of Howard Cosell|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pRirlKfG3J0C&pg=PA153&dq=ABC+Sports+Boxing&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjOhp6EkozkAhULEawKHYzfBE44KBDoATACegQIBBAC#v=onepage&q=ABC%20Sports%20Boxing&f=false|location= |publisher=Univ of Massachusetts Press|page=153|isbn= |author-link=}}</ref>. Halfway through the bout and with Cobb absorbing a beating, Cosell stopped providing anything more than rudimentary comments about round number and the participants punctuated with occasional declarations of disgust during the 15 rounds. He declared shortly after the fight to a national television audience that he had broadcast his last professional boxing match.\n\nIn the [[Boxing at the 1976 Summer Olympics|1976 Summer Games in Montreal]], and the [[Boxing at the 1984 Summer Olympics|1984 games in Los Angeles]], Cosell was the main voice for boxing. [[Sugar Ray Leonard]] won the gold medal in his light welterweight class at Montreal, beginning his meteoric rise to a world professional title a few years later, and Cosell became close to Leonard, during this period, announcing many of his fights.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">\"I Never Played The Game\", by Howard Cosell, 1985</ref>\n\n===Cancelled 2007 card===\n{{see also|Boxing on ESPN}}\n\nSeven years after ABC's last boxing card, they were scheduled to broadcast a card from [[Boardwalk Hall]] in [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]] on April 22, 2007. The card would've featured former light heavyweight champion [[Antonio Tarver]] facing off against [[Elvir Muriqi]]. Promoter Joe DeGuardia of Star Boxing had been working on the [[Brokered programming|time buy]] deal (in other words, DeGuardia was not paid a licensing fee by ABC, but rather bought an hour of time from the network). The production would've been handled by ABC's sister company, [[ESPN]] with ''[[Friday Night Fights]]'' commentators [[Joe Tessitore]] and [[Teddy Atlas]]. The bout was ultimately scrapped<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tss.ib.tv/boxing/articles-of-2007/5142-antonio-tarver-master-of-second-chances|title=Antonio Tarver: Master Of Second Chances|last=Keenan|first=Ronan|date=June 4, 2007|website=The Sweet Science|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> amid rumors that Tarver would not be able to make the 175 pound weight limit.\n\n===''Premier Boxing Champions'' (2015)===\nOn March 19, 2015, ESPN announced that ''Friday Night Fights'' would air for the final time on May 22, 2015, covering the finals of the 2015 Boxcino tournament. The network announced that it had reached a multi-year deal with [[Al Haymon]]'s ''[[Premier Boxing Champions]]'' to broadcast 11 events per-year on the main ESPN network, primarily on Saturday nights, and an afternoon event on [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]]. [[Joe Tessitore]] and [[Teddy Atlas]] were carried over to serve as hosts. ESPN is one of several major broadcasters that airs fights through the promotion, which also includes [[NBC]], [[CBS]], their respective cable sports networks, as well as [[Spike (TV network)|Spike]].<ref name=deadline-pbcespn>{{cite web|title=ESPN Joins Premier Boxing Champions\u2019 Corner, Knocking Out \u2018Friday Night Fights\u2019|url=https://deadline.com/2015/03/espn-premier-boxing-champions-friday-night-fights-ending-1201394575/|website=[Deadline.com|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|accessdate=March 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*''[[ABC Wide World of Sports Boxing]]''\n*[[Boxing on the radio]]\n*[[Olympics_on_ABC_commentators#Summer_Olympics]]\n*[[The Super Fight]] - Debates subsequently took place over the next three decades as to whether at least one print of film had survived. It was cited that many theaters had continued to play the film long after January 20, 1970, and was also noted that the film had one airing on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Wide World of Sports (US TV series)|Wide World of Sports]]'' in 1970, and another on [[CBS]] late night in 1977, with many more broadcasts alleged throughout.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.espn.com/abcsports/wwos/highlights/boxing.html Wide World Boxing Milestones and Highlights]\n**[http://espn.go.com/abcsports/wwos/milestones/1960s.html ''Wide World of Sports'' Highlights -- 1960s]\n**[http://espn.go.com/abcsports/wwos/milestones/1970s.html ''Wide World of Sports'' Highlights -- 1970s]\n**[http://espn.go.com/abcsports/wwos/milestones/1980s.html ''Wide World of Sports'' Highlights -- 1980s]\n**[http://espn.go.com/abcsports/wwos/milestones/1990s.html ''Wide World of Sports'' Highlights -- 1990s]\n**[http://imasportsphile.com/category/wide-world-of-sports/ Wide World of Sports \u2013 ImaSportsphile]\n*[https://abcnews.go.com/search?searchtext=Boxing ABC News - Boxing]\n*[http://www.skypoint.com/members/schutz19/boxing.htm BOXING ON TV]\n\n{{ESPN on ABC}}\n{{ABC's Wide World of Sports}}\n{{Boxing on television}}\n{{Boxing on ABC}}\n\n[[Category:Wide World of Sports (American TV series)]]\n[[Category:ABC Sports]]\n[[Category:Boxing television series|ABC]]\n[[Category:American Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:1940s American television series]]\n[[Category:1950s American television series]]\n[[Category:1960s American television series]]\n[[Category:1970s American television series]]\n[[Category:1980s American television series]]\n[[Category:1990s American television series]]\n[[