{"title_page": "Ingrid Andress", "text_new": "{{short description|American country music singer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Ingrid Andress\n| image            = \n| image_upright    = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Ingrid Elizabeth Andress\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1991|09|21}}\n| birth_place      = [[Southfield, Michigan]], U.S.<ref name=Birthplace>{{cite web | url=https://wycd.radio.com/articles/ingrid-andress-reveals-her-birthplace-to-rob-and-holly | title=Ingrid Andress Reveals Her Birthplace To Rob And Holly Before Her Ten Man Jam Performance | publisher=99.5 WYCD | date=13 February 2020 | accessdate=13 February 2020 | author=Rob and Holly}}</ref>\n| origin           = [[Nashville, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| genre            = [[Country music|Country]]\n| occupation       = Singer-songwriter\n| instrument       = Vocals, piano\n| years_active     = 2019-present\n| label            = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]] / [[Warner Records|Warner Nashville]]\n| associated_acts  = \n}}\n'''Ingrid Elizabeth Andress''' (born September 21, 1991) is an American [[country music]] singer from Colorado. Her debut single \"More Hearts Than Mine\" debuted at number 59 on the ''Billboard'' [[Country Airplay]] chart dated July 1, 2019. In March 2020, she released her first album ''Lady Like''.\n\n==Life and career==\nAndress was born in [[Southfield, Michigan]]<ref name=Birthplace/> and grew up in [[Highlands Ranch, Colorado]]. As a child, she learned to play piano and drums while also participating in high school choir competitions. Andress attended [[Berklee College of Music]] and majored in songwriting and performance.<ref name=bio />\n\nShe founded an [[a cappella]] group called Pitch Slapped, which performed on the [[NBC]] singing competition ''[[The Sing-Off]]''. Another one of her groups, Delilah, also performed on the show and placed sixth. After leaving the show, Andress finished her degree and underwent a mentorship with pop songwriter [[Kara DioGuardi]]. She then moved to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] where she began writing songs for artists such as [[Sam Hunt]], [[Alicia Keys]], and [[Charli XCX]].<ref name=bio>{{cite web | url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/ingrid-andress-mn0002596016/biography | title=Ingrid Andress biography | publisher=AllMusic | accessdate=October 20, 2019 | author=Matt Collar}}</ref>\n\nAndress signed with [[Warner Records|Warner Nashville]] in mid 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://musicrow.com/2018/07/ingrid-andress-signs-with-warner-music-nashville-atlantic-records/ | title=Ingrid Andress Signs With Warner Music Nashville, Atlantic Records | work=MusicRow | date=July 27, 2018 | accessdate=October 20, 2019 | author=Lorie Hollabaugh}}</ref> In 2019, she debuted with the single \"[[More Hearts Than Mine]]\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://tasteofcountry.com/ingrid-andress-more-hearts-than-mine-interview/ | title=Ingrid Andress Parents' Perfect Reaction to More Hearts Than Mine | work=Taste of Country | date=August 26, 2019 | accessdate=October 20, 2019 | author=Billy Dukes}}</ref> The song has charted on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Songs]] and [[Country Airplay]] charts. Andress cites [[Faith Hill]] and the [[Dixie Chicks]] as her musical inspirations, and notes that she always wants to write her own songs unless she finds an exceptional song written by someone else.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://theboot.com/ingrid-andress-music-sound/ | title=Ingrid Andress: 'I Just Feel Like Keeping It Open-Minded' | publisher=The Boot | date=July 23, 2019 | accessdate=October 20, 2019 | author=Carena Liptak}}</ref> On March 27, 2020, she released her debut studio album Lady Like through Warner Music Nashville.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/9343148/ingrid-andress-lady-like-album-breakdown|title=Ingrid Andress&#39; &#39;Lady Like&#39; Album: Stories Behind the Songs|date=2020-03-26|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nAndress ascended to No. 1 on Billboard's Emerging Artists chart in April 2020 which is due to the chart arrival of her debut studio album, ''Lady Like'', and the rise of her single \"More Hearts Than Mine\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9353831/ingrid-andress-tops-emerging-artists-chart |title=Leading 'Lady': Ingrid Andress Hits No. 1 on Emerging Artists Chart |date=2020-04-08 |website=billboard.com |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:8em;\"| Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:17em;\"| Details\n! colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! style=\"width:4em;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br /><ref>{{cite web |title=Ingrid Andress Chart History (Billboard 200) |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Ingrid-Andress/chart-history/TLP |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:4em;\"| [[Top Country Albums|US Country]]<br /><ref>{{cite web |title=Ingrid Andress Chart History (Top Country Albums) |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Ingrid-Andress/chart-history/CLP |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Lady Like]]''\n|\n* Release date: March 27, 2020\n* Label: [[Warner Music Nashville]]\n* Format: [[Compact disc|CD]], [[Music download|digital download]]\n| 90 || 9\n|}\n\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''The Rosebank Acoustic Sessions''\n* Release date: September 16, 2019\n* Label: [[Atlantic Nashville]]\n* Format: music download\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"widt