{"title_page": "Harry Hood (footballer)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| image        =\n| caption      =\n| name         = Harry Hood\n| fullname     = Henry Anthony Hood<ref>{{Hugman|9303|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=heraldobit/>\n| height       = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date|df=yes|1944|10|3}}\n| birth_place  = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|df=yes|2019|5|26|1944|10|3}}\n| death_place  = \n| position     = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[St Roch's F.C.|St Roch's]]\n| years1 = 1962\u20131964\n| years2 = 1964\u20131966\n| years3 = 1966\u20131969\n| years4 = 1969\u20131976\n| years5 = 1976\n| years6 = 1976\u20131977\n| years7 = 1977\u20131978\n| clubs1 = [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]]\n| clubs2 = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n| clubs3 = [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]]\n| clubs4 = [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]\n| clubs5 = [[San Antonio Thunder]]\n| clubs6 = [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]]\n| clubs7 = [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]]\n| caps1 = 63  | goals1 = 40\n| caps2 = 31  | goals2 = 9\n| caps3 = 87  | goals3 = 30\n| caps4 = 189 | goals4 = 74\n| caps5 = 20  | goals5 = 10\n| caps6 = 15  | goals6 = 0\n| caps7 = 32  | goals7 = 4\n| totalcaps = 436\n| totalgoals= 166\n<!--STATS ACCOUNT FOR LEAGUE ONLY-->\n| nationalyears1= 1967\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland XI]]<ref name=rsssf>{{cite web|author=Stephen Bell; Andre Zlotkowski  |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/scotlandxi-asotour67.html|title=Scotland XI Tour of Asia and Oceania 1967|publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]]|date=6 June 2008 |accessdate=7 April 2011}}</ref> \n| nationalcaps1 = 4\n| nationalgoals1= 1\n| nationalyears2= 1970\n| nationalteam2 = [[Scottish League XI]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.londonhearts.com/SFL/players/harryhood.html|title=Harry Hood|work=Londonhearts.com|publisher=London Hearts Supporters' Club|accessdate=11 December 2011}}</ref>\n| nationalcaps2 = 1\n| nationalgoals2= 0\n| nationalyears3= 1968\n| nationalteam3 = [[Scotland national under-23 football team|Scotland U23]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/scotlandu23/player.php?playerid=134|title=Hood, Harry (Scotland U23)|publisher=fitbastats.com|accessdate=1 November 2012}}</ref>\n| nationalcaps3 = 1\n| nationalgoals3= 1\n| manageryears1 = 1981 \n| manageryears2 = 1981\u20131982\n| managerclubs1 = [[Albion Rovers F.C.|Albion Rovers]] \n| managerclubs2 = [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]]\n}}\n'''Henry Anthony Hood''' (3 October 1944 \u2013 26 May 2019) was a Scottish [[Association football|football]] player and [[manager (association football)|manager]].\n\nA [[forward (association football)|forward]] noted for his skill,<ref name=heraldobit/><ref name=bbcobit/><ref name=Celticobit/> he played for [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]] (two spells), [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]]\nand [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] in Scotland, [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in England and [[San Antonio Thunder]]\nin the United States. He won eleven domestic honours with Celtic.<ref name=bbcobit/><ref name=clydehof/> He later managed [[Albion Rovers F.C.|Albion Rovers]] and Queen of the South, and was a businessman involved in the hospitality sector.\n\n==Football career==\nBorn in [[Glasgow]] and raised in the city's [[Garthamlock]] neighbourhood,<ref name=heraldobit/> Hood's older brother [[Jackie Hood|Jackie]] was also a footballer<ref name=England>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecelticwiki.com/m/page/Hood%2C+Harry |title=A spell in England is good experience |accessdate=26 May 2019 |work=International Football Book No 12|year=1970|via=The Celtic Wiki}}</ref> who won the [[Liverpool Senior Cup]] while a reserve player at [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bluecorrespondent.co.uk/1956-57/may1957.html |title=Mortensen's 4-minute shock goal |date=11 May 1957 |accessdate=27 May 2019 |publisher=[[Liverpool Echo]]|via=Blue Correspondent}}</ref> but had returned to Scotland and local [[Scottish Junior Football Association|Junior]] club [[St Roch's F.C.|St Roch's]] by the time his younger sibling was starting his career. Harry Hood initially attended school at [[St Aloysius' College, Glasgow|St Aloysius College]] where [[rugby union]] was the chosen sport.<ref name=England/><ref name=heraldobit/> Seeking a schoolboy appearance for Scotland, he moved to [[Holyrood Secondary School]] but was overlooked for the national schoolboy squad as he had already registered as a senior player at St Roch's.<ref name=England/>\n\nIn summer 1962 he signed for [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]], making his [[Scottish Division One]] debut in November of that year, aged 18.<ref name=clydeobit>{{cite web |url=https://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2019/05/26/6129/#.XOt7ZGbVxkg |title=News: Harry Hood |date=26 May 2019 |accessdate=27 May 2019 |publisher=Clyde FC}}</ref> Clyde were relegated to the second tier, but in the lower division Hood flourished, scoring 37 times from 45 appearances in all competitions during the [[1963\u201364 in Scottish football|1963\u201364 season]] as the club gained promotion.<ref name=clydeobit/> This good form continued into the next campaign and, after hesitating over a move to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], the team he had supported in childhood,<ref name=England/> he was transferred to English club [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] for a fee of \u00a330,000 in November 1964.<ref name=clydeobit/> In an early outing for the [[Roker Park]] club, Hood scored the only goal of the match against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]],<ref name=clydehof/> but overall his spell in England was not particularly successful and in October 1966 he returned to Clyde for \u00a313,000. The [[1966\u201367 Scottish Division One]] season proved to be one of the best in the club's history as they finished in 3rd position, behind only [[European Cup]] winners [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] and [[European Cup Winners' Cup]] finalists [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]].<ref name=clydehof/> That summer Hood was a member of an unofficial [[Scotland national football team|Scotland party]] which travelled to destinations including Israel, Australia and Canada, winning every match.<ref name=rsssf/> However, like fellow squad member[[Alex Ferguson]], Hood would never be [[Cap (sports)|capped]] at full international level.<ref name=clydehof/>\n\nHood signed for Celtic in March 1969 for a \u00a340,000 transfer fee,<ref name=clydehof/> and quickly established himself in a talented group managed by [[Jock Stein]] including the Europe-conquering [[Lisbon Lions]] and the emerging highly rated youth players such as [[Kenny Dalglish]] dubbed the [[Quality Street Gang]].<ref name=Celticobit/><ref name=bbcobit/> After playing a part in the team's run to the [[1970 European Cup Final]],<ref name=fscfc/> he was not selected for the match in [[Milan]] as Celtic lost to [[Feyenoord]]. He scored the winning goal against Rangers in the [[1971 Scottish Cup Final]] replay as Celtic won 2\u20131, and also scored the first goal in the [[1974 Scottish Cup Final]], a 3\u20130 victory over [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]].<ref name=fscfc>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/celtic/player.php?playerid=2689 |title=Celtic player Harry Hood |date= |accessdate=27 May 2019 |website=FitbaStats}}</ref>\n\nWith Celtic, Hood won six [[List of Scottish football champions|Scottish league championships]], three [[Scottish Cup]]s and two [[Scottish League Cup]]s;<ref name=Celticobit>{{cite web |url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/15993 |title=Sad passing of Celtic great, Harry Hood |first=Paul |last=Cuddihy |date=26 May 2019 |accessdate=26 May 2019 |publisher=Celtic FC}}</ref> He scored 123 goals in all major competitions for the club. His presence onto the field at [[Celtic Park|Parkhead]] was often greeted with a [[Hare Krishna (mantra)|'Hare Krishna']] chant.<ref name=heraldobit>{{cite web |url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/17665621.obituary-harry-hood-celtic-star/ |title=Obituary: Harry Hood, Celtic star |date=26 May 2019 |accessdate=26 May 2019 |publisher=The Herald}}</ref> Hood scored a hat-trick in an [[Old Firm]] game against Rangers in 1973,<ref name = \"rangers\">{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/celtic/celtic-s-last-old-firm-hat-trick-hero-unafraid-1-3671647 |title=Celtic's last Old Firm hat-trick hero 'unafraid' |first=Lindsay |last=Herron |date=28 January 2015 |accessdate=11 September 2016}}</ref> a feat that was not repeated until [[Moussa Demb\u00e9l\u00e9 (French footballer)|Moussa Demb\u00e9l\u00e9]] achieved it in 2016.<ref name = \"rangers\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37263899 |title=Celtic 5\u20131 Rangers |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=10 September 2016 |accessdate=11 September 2016 |first=Tom |last=English}}</ref>\n\nHood left Celtic in 1976 and, after short spells with [[San Antonio Thunder]] in the [[North American Soccer League|NASL]]<ref name=clydehof/> and [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]], ended his playing career with [[Dumfries]] club [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] in season 1977\u201378.<ref name=heraldobit/> After a spell managing [[Albion Rovers F.C.|Albion Rovers]], Hood returned to ''Queens'' in the summer of 1981 as manager, just after the club had been promoted to the [[Scottish Football League First Division|First Division]].<ref>[http://qosfc.com/AboutQueens/ClubHistory/tabid/164/Default.aspx Club History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228215122/http://www.qosfc.com/AboutQueens/ClubHistory/tabid/164/Default.aspx/ |date=28 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Later years==\nAfter his retirement from football, Hood ran a company (named ''Lisini'', incorporating the names of his three children)<ref name=heraldobit/> which owned and ran several public houses and restaurants in the [[Greater Glasgow]] area.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-21924420 |title=SPL faces \u00a31.7m claim over 'foreign broadcast' dispute |publisher=BBC News |date=25 March 2013 |accessdate=}}</ref><ref name=bbcobit/> In 2012, he was inducted into the Clyde FC Hall of Fame.<ref name=clydehof>{{cite web |url=https://www.clydefc.co.uk/club/history/hall-of-fame/harry-hood/ |title=Hall of Fame: Harry Hood |date= |accessdate=27 May 2019 |publisher=Clyde FC}}</ref>\n\nAfter a battle with cancer, Hood died around 6:30am on 26 May 2019, aged 74.<ref name=bbcobit>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48413675 |title=Harry Hood: Former Celtic, Clyde and Sunderland forward Harry Hood dies |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=26 May 2019 |accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Celtic'''<ref name=heraldobit/><ref name=Celticobit/><ref name=fscfc/>\n*[[List of Scottish football champions|Scottish League]] (6): [[1968\u201369 Scottish Division One|1968\u201369]], [[1969\u201370 Scottish Division One|1969\u201370]], [[1970\u201371 Scottish Division One|1970\u201371]], [[1971\u201372 Scottish Division One|1971\u201372]], [[1972\u201373 Scottish Division One|1972\u201373]], [[1973\u201374 Scottish Division One|1973\u201374]]\n*[[Scottish Cup]] (3): [[1970\u201371 Scottish Cup|1970\u201371]], [[1973\u201374 Scottish Cup|1973\u201374]], [[1974\u201375 Scottish Cup|1974\u201375]]\n*[[Scottish League Cup]]: [[1969\u201370 Scottish League Cup|1969\u201370]], [[1974\u201375 Scottish League Cup|1974\u201375]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Scottish Division One]] top goalscorer: [[1970\u201371 in Scottish football|1970\u201371]]<ref name=heraldobit/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{NeilBrownPlayers|player/harryhood}}\n\n{{Scottish First Division top scorers}}\n{{Albion Rovers F.C. managers}}\n{{Queen of the South F.C. managers}}\n{{Clyde F.C. Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hood, Harry}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Aloysius' College, Glasgow]]\n[[Category:People educated at Holyrood Secondary School]]\n[[Category:Albion Rovers F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:St Roch's F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Junior Football Association players]]\n[[Category:Celtic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Clyde F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Motherwell F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Queen of the South F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Queen of the South F.C. players]]\n[[Category:San Antonio Thunder players]]\n[[Category:Scotland under-23 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:Scottish football managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:North American Soccer League (1968\u20131984) players]]\n[[Category:Scottish league football top scorers]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| image        =\n| caption      =\n| name         = Harry Hood\n| fullname     = Henry Anthony Hood<ref>{{Hugman|9303|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=heraldobit/>\n| height       = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date|df=yes|1944|10|3}}\n| birth_place  = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|df=yes|2019|5|26|1944|10|3}}\n| death_place  = \n| position     = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[St Roch's F.C.|St Roch's]]\n| years1 = 1962\u20131964\n| years2 = 1964\u20131966\n| years3 = 1966\u20131969\n| years4 = 1969\u20131976\n| years5 = 1976\n| years6 = 1976\u20131977\n| years7 = 1977\u20131978\n| clubs1 = [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]]\n| clubs2 = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n| clubs3 = [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]]\n| clubs4 = [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]\n| clubs5 = [[San Antonio Thunder]]\n| clubs6 = [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]]\n| clubs7 = [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]]\n| caps1 = 63  | goals1 = 40\n| caps2 = 31  | goals2 = 9\n| caps3 = 87  | goals3 = 30\n| caps4 = 188 | goals4 = 73\n| caps5 = 20  | goals5 = 10\n| caps6 = 15  | goals6 = 0\n| caps7 = 32  | goals7 = 4\n| totalcaps = 436\n| totalgoals= 166\n<!--STATS ACCOUNT FOR LEAGUE ONLY-->\n| nationalyears1= 1967\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland XI]]<ref name=rsssf>{{cite web|author=Stephen Bell; Andre Zlotkowski  |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/scotlandxi-asotour67.html|title=Scotland XI Tour of Asia and Oceania 1967|publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]]|date=6 June 2008 |accessdate=7 April 2011}}</ref> \n| nationalcaps1 = 4\n| nationalgoals1= 1\n| nationalyears2= 1970\n| nationalteam2 = [[Scottish League XI]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.londonhearts.com/SFL/players/harryhood.html|title=Harry Hood|work=Londonhearts.com|publisher=London Hearts Supporters' Club|accessdate=11 December 2011}}</ref>\n| nationalcaps2 = 1\n| nationalgoals2= 0\n| nationalyears3= 1968\n| nationalteam3 = [[Scotland national under-23 football team|Scotland U23]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/scotlandu23/player.php?playerid=134|title=Hood, Harry (Scotland U23)|publisher=fitbastats.com|accessdate=1 November 2012}}</ref>\n| nationalcaps3 = 1\n| nationalgoals3= 1\n| manageryears1 = 1981 \n| manageryears2 = 1981\u20131982\n| managerclubs1 = [[Albion Rovers F.C.|Albion Rovers]] \n| managerclubs2 = [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]]\n}}\n'''Henry Anthony Hood''' (3 October 1944 \u2013 26 May 2019) was a Scottish [[Association football|football]] player and [[manager (association football)|manager]].\n\nA [[forward (association football)|forward]] noted for his skill,<ref name=heraldobit/><ref name=bbcobit/><ref name=Celticobit/> he played for [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]] (two spells), [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]]\nand [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] in Scotland, [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in England and [[San Antonio Thunder]]\nin the United States. He won eleven domestic honours with Celtic.<ref name=bbcobit/><ref name=clydehof/> He later managed [[Albion Rovers F.C.|Albion Rovers]] and Queen of the South, and was a businessman involved in the hospitality sector.\n\n==Football career==\nBorn in [[Glasgow]] and raised in the city's [[Garthamlock]] neighbourhood,<ref name=heraldobit/> Hood's older brother [[Jackie Hood|Jackie]] was also a footballer<ref name=England>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecelticwiki.com/m/page/Hood%2C+Harry |title=A spell in England is good experience |accessdate=26 May 2019 |work=International Football Book No 12|year=1970|via=The Celtic Wiki}}</ref> who won the [[Liverpool Senior Cup]] while a reserve player at [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bluecorrespondent.co.uk/1956-57/may1957.html |title=Mortensen's 4-minute shock goal |date=11 May 1957 |accessdate=27 May 2019 |publisher=[[Liverpool Echo]]|via=Blue Correspondent}}</ref> but had returned to Scotland and local [[Scottish Junior Football Association|Junior]] club [[St Roch's F.C.|St Roch's]] by the time his younger sibling was starting his career. Harry Hood initially attended school at [[St Aloysius' College, Glasgow|St Aloysius College]] where [[rugby union]] was the chosen sport.<ref name=England/><ref name=heraldobit/> Seeking a schoolboy appearance for Scotland, he moved to [[Holyrood Secondary School]] but was overlooked for the national schoolboy squad as he had already registered as a senior player at St Roch's.<ref name=England/>\n\nIn summer 1962 he signed for [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]], making his [[Scottish Division One]] debut in November of that year, aged 18.<ref name=clydeobit>{{cite web |url=https://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2019/05/26/6129/#.XOt7ZGbVxkg |title=News: Harry Hood |date=26 May 2019 |accessdate=27 May 2019 |publisher=Clyde FC}}</ref> Clyde were relegated to the second tier, but in the lower division Hood flourished, scoring 37 times from 45 appearances in all competitions during the [[1963\u201364 in Scottish football|1963\u201364 season]] as the club gained promotion.<ref name=clydeobit/> This good form continued into the next campaign and, after hesitating over a move to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], the team he had supported in childhood,<ref name=England/> he was transferred to English club [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] for a fee of \u00a330,000 in November 1964.<ref name=clydeobit/> In an early outing for the [[Roker Park]] club, Hood scored the only goal of the match against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]],<ref name=clydehof/> but overall his spell in England was not particularly successful and in October 1966 he returned to Clyde for \u00a313,000. The [[1966\u201367 Scottish Division One]] season proved to be one of the best in the club's history as they finished in 3rd position, behind only [[European Cup]] winners [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] and [[European Cup Winners' Cup]] finalists [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]].<ref name=clydehof/> That summer Hood was a member of an unofficial [[Scotland national football team|Scotland party]] which travelled to destinations including Israel, Australia and Canada, winning every match.<ref name=rsssf/> However, like fellow squad member[[Alex Ferguson]], Hood would never be [[Cap (sports)|capped]] at full international level.<ref name=clydehof/>\n\nHood signed for Celtic in March 1969 for a \u00a340,000 transfer fee,<ref name=clydehof/> and quickly established himself in a talented group managed by [[Jock Stein]] including the Europe-conquering [[Lisbon Lions]] and the emerging highly rated youth players such as [[Kenny Dalglish]] dubbed the [[Quality Street Gang]].<ref name=Celticobit/><ref name=bbcobit/> After playing a part in the team's run to the [[1970 European Cup Final]],<ref name=fscfc/> he was not selected for the match in [[Milan]] as Celtic lost to [[Feyenoord]]. He scored the winning goal against Rangers in the [[1971 Scottish Cup Final]] replay as Celtic won 2\u20131, and also scored the first goal in the [[1974 Scottish Cup Final]], a 3\u20130 victory over [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]].<ref name=fscfc>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/celtic/player.php?playerid=2689 |title=Celtic player Harry Hood |date= |accessdate=27 May 2019 |website=FitbaStats}}</ref>\n\nWith Celtic, Hood won six [[List of Scottish football champions|Scottish league championships]], three [[Scottish Cup]]s and two [[Scottish League Cup]]s;<ref name=Celticobit>{{cite web |url=http://www.celticfc.net/news/15993 |title=Sad passing of Celtic great, Harry Hood |first=Paul |last=Cuddihy |date=26 May 2019 |accessdate=26 May 2019 |publisher=Celtic FC}}</ref> He scored 123 goals in all major competitions for the club. His presence onto the field at [[Celtic Park|Parkhead]] was often greeted with a [[Hare Krishna (mantra)|'Hare Krishna']] chant.<ref name=heraldobit>{{cite web |url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/17665621.obituary-harry-hood-celtic-star/ |title=Obituary: Harry Hood, Celtic star |date=26 May 2019 |accessdate=26 May 2019 |publisher=The Herald}}</ref> Hood scored a hat-trick in an [[Old Firm]] game against Rangers in 1973,<ref name = \"rangers\">{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/celtic/celtic-s-last-old-firm-hat-trick-hero-unafraid-1-3671647 |title=Celtic's last Old Firm hat-trick hero 'unafraid' |first=Lindsay |last=Herron |date=28 January 2015 |accessdate=11 September 2016}}</ref> a feat that was not repeated until [[Moussa Demb\u00e9l\u00e9 (French footballer)|Moussa Demb\u00e9l\u00e9]] achieved it in 2016.<ref name = \"rangers\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37263899 |title=Celtic 5\u20131 Rangers |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=10 September 2016 |accessdate=11 September 2016 |first=Tom |last=English}}</ref>\n\nHood left Celtic in 1976 and, after short spells with [[San Antonio Thunder]] in the [[North American Soccer League|NASL]]<ref name=clydehof/> and [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]], ended his playing career with [[Dumfries]] club [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] in season 1977\u201378.<ref name=heraldobit/> After a spell managing [[Albion Rovers F.C.|Albion Rovers]], Hood returned to ''Queens'' in the summer of 1981 as manager, just after the club had been promoted to the [[Scottish Football League First Division|First Division]].<ref>[http://qosfc.com/AboutQueens/ClubHistory/tabid/164/Default.aspx Club History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228215122/http://www.qosfc.com/AboutQueens/ClubHistory/tabid/164/Default.aspx/ |date=28 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Later years==\nAfter his retirement from football, Hood ran a company (named ''Lisini'', incorporating the names of his three children)<ref name=heraldobit/> which owned and ran several public houses and restaurants in the [[Greater Glasgow]] area.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-21924420 |title=SPL faces \u00a31.7m claim over 'foreign broadcast' dispute |publisher=BBC News |date=25 March 2013 |accessdate=}}</ref><ref name=bbcobit/> In 2012, he was inducted into the Clyde FC Hall of Fame.<ref name=clydehof>{{cite web |url=https://www.clydefc.co.uk/club/history/hall-of-fame/harry-hood/ |title=Hall of Fame: Harry Hood |date= |accessdate=27 May 2019 |publisher=Clyde FC}}</ref>\n\nAfter a battle with cancer, Hood died around 6:30am on 26 May 2019, aged 74.<ref name=bbcobit>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48413675 |title=Harry Hood: Former Celtic, Clyde and Sunderland forward Harry Hood dies |work= |publisher=BBC Sport |date=26 May 2019 |accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Celtic'''<ref name=heraldobit/><ref name=Celticobit/><ref name=fscfc/>\n*[[List of Scottish football champions|Scottish League]] (6): [[1968\u201369 Scottish Division One|1968\u201369]], [[1969\u201370 Scottish Division One|1969\u201370]], [[1970\u201371 Scottish Division One|1970\u201371]], [[1971\u201372 Scottish Division One|1971\u201372]], [[1972\u201373 Scottish Division One|1972\u201373]], [[1973\u201374 Scottish Division One|1973\u201374]]\n*[[Scottish Cup]] (3): [[1970\u201371 Scottish Cup|1970\u201371]], [[1973\u201374 Scottish Cup|1973\u201374]], [[1974\u201375 Scottish Cup|1974\u201375]]\n*[[Scottish League Cup]]: [[1969\u201370 Scottish League Cup|1969\u201370]], [[1974\u201375 Scottish League Cup|1974\u201375]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Scottish Division One]] top goalscorer: [[1970\u201371 in Scottish football|1970\u201371]]<ref name=heraldobit/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{NeilBrownPlayers|player/harryhood}}\n\n{{Scottish First Division top scorers}}\n{{Albion Rovers F.C. managers}}\n{{Queen of the South F.C. managers}}\n{{Clyde F.C. Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hood, Harry}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Aloysius' College, Glasgow]]\n[[Category:People educated at Holyrood Secondary School]]\n[[Category:Albion Rovers F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:St Roch's F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Junior Football Association players]]\n[[Category:Celtic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Clyde F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Motherwell F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Queen of the South F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Queen of the South F.C. players]]\n[[Category:San Antonio Thunder players]]\n[[Category:Scotland under-23 inter